\par\par \b \uc2  MODERATE RISE IN STATE  \highlight22\uc2 BUDGET \highlight\uc2  STILL FEASIBLE - HOUSE MEMBERS. \b0\par\par\uc2 700 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 November 1994\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1994 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): A moderate 15 to 20 percent rise in the 1995-96 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still feasible despite the government's grim outlook on domestic resources, say members of the Budgetary Commission of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR). \par \par \uc2  Speaking at the conclusion of a four-day preliminary deliberation on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for 1995-96, all of the commission's four factions agreed that there is still much room for \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion. \par \par \uc2  Factions of the ruling Golongan Karya (Golkar) and Armed Forces believe that prices of crude oil will reach an average of US$17 per barrel next year, even though Iraq could re-enter the world's oil market during that period. \par \par \uc2  "The price of natural gas, which is related to developments in crude oil prices, will automatically be boosted," R.P. Soebagio, spokesman for the Golkar faction, said about the reason behind his faction's optimism. \par \par \uc2  The government's \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipts from the oil and gas sector are projected to reach Rp 12.85 trillion (US$5.9 billion) this \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year, accounting for around 18.5 percent of the total 1994-95 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The receipt projection is calculated on an average price of $16 per barrel. \par \par \uc2  Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad said earlier that the 1995-96 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be kept at the same level as that for this \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year not only due to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the world's oil market but also because of the expected flat growth in receipts from non-oil sectors. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  He said that the government's decision to lower income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates beginning next year would limit the growth of the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipts outside the oil and gas sector, which are estimated to reach Rp 46.88 trillion in the present \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  The receipts from non-oil sectors have become more important in the last five years not only due to the government's determination to reduce foreign debts but also due to the country's declining oil \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Indonesia's oil production - including condensate - has reached its maximum level of 1.5 million barrels per day. \par \par \uc2  The factions of Golkar, the Armed Forces and the Moslem-dominated United Development Party (PPP) feel that an increase of around 15 percent is still possible. In addition, the government's commitment to stronger law enforcement and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion should further raise the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  coverage ratio, thereby offsetting the negative impact of the reduction of the income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  tariffs. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) said that the rise should be around 20 percent as the increase of around 10 percent would cover only the losses caused by inflation, which is not expected to surpass nine percent. \par \par \uc2  The PPP and PDI factions, however, warned the government to work harder to improve the business climate and also to encourage more foreign and local investments. \par \par \uc2  The two factions believe the role of the private sector will be more dominant in the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a larger portion of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be used mainly for the government's routine expenditures. \par \par \uc2  Sa'di Zen Noor, spokesman for the PPP faction, said that the government should watch the inflow of foreign debts more carefully, both for government agencies and the private sector. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's external debts have reached a stunning level of $93 billion, making the country the third largest borrower in the world. Around 60 percent of the total debts are owed by the government and the remaining 40 percent by the private sector. \par \par \uc2  Sa'di said that the government should restrict private borrowing because a further increase would hurt the whole \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government's foreign debt reached a total of $56.84 billion as of August this year, $7.31 billion (around 12.9 percent) coming from the United States, $25.23 billion (44.4 percent) from Japan, $2.93 billion (5.2 percent) from Germany, $10.08 billion (17.7 percent) from the World Bank, $4.38 billion (around 7.7 percent) from the Asian Development Bank (ADB) and the remaining 6.9 billion (12.1 percent) from other financial institutions and donor countries.(hen) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1994 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011105dqbb001g8\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
