\par\par \b \uc2  ASIA TOLD TO CLOSE RANKS TO FACE WORLD COMPETITION. \b0\par\par\uc2 510 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 December 1994\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1994 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  KUALA LUMPUR (JP): Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim is inviting Asian nations to close ranks to improve competitiveness in facing the increasing global business competition following the implementation of the GATT principles. \par \par \uc2  "Asian countries will have to break away from narrow nationalistic thought-paths to pursue with greater enthusiasm aregional and global agenda," he said in a two-day conference at the Hilton hotel which ended yesterday. \par \par \uc2  He said the ratification of the General Agreements on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) by its signatories has practically sealed the fate of inward-looking policies, in favor of freer and more open markets, which will further enhance the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects of individual Asian countries. \par \par \uc2  The new GATT principles are scheduled to be implemented early next month under the administration of the newly-established World Trade Organization. \par \par \uc2  "But the challenge before Asia at this point in time is not simply to grow as an aggregate of separate individual economies but as a more integrated regional entity," Anwar said. "We need to strengthen the building blocks of a regional Asia." \par \par \uc2  He suggested that Asian governments reengineer \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies to overcome numerous internal constraints and to astutely cushion the impact of externally generated \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and risks. \par \par \uc2  Reforms must be instituted to fortify \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals, while private sector initiatives must be given more room to generate growth and to spur the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to greater heights, said Anwar, who is also Malaysian minister of finance. \par \par \uc2  Climate \par \par \uc2  The investment climate should be made more robust through deregulation and privatization and appropriate policies must be formulated to widen the industrial base in order to expand the export potential of the resultant industries, Anwar told 150 business people participating in the seminar, entitled Global Asia: Reengineering for Competitive Advantage, which was organized by the Far Eastern \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Review \par \par \uc2  Jeffrey Sachs, a professor of the U.S. Harvard University, told the meeting that countries wanting to increase their competitiveness should make improvements in the fields of macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , labor costs, \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  systems and capital, while improving the development of human resources and the decentralization of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Certainty \par \par \uc2  The laws of the countries should also provide business certainty, he said. \par \par \uc2  Amnuay Viravan, the leader of the Nam Thai Party of Thailand, told the conference that in this era of globalization, governments and the business sectors in Asia should forge astrong and strategic alliance to improve efficiency. \par \par \uc2  The governments, for example, should adopt development, infrastructure, legal, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary frameworks and policies designed to facilitate the private sectors' investments and initiatives and upgrade the quality of human resources. \par \par \uc2  The governments should also pursue programs of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  liberalization and deregulation to promote competition as well as bring about necessary political reforms to attract younger, more educated generations to political careers in order to ensure the quality of political leadership over the longer term. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the business sectors should strive for asustainable increase in efficiency through significant investment in human resource development and research and development activities, he said. (riz) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1994 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011105dqce0024b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
