\par\par \b \uc2  NU LEADER ABU HASAN CAUGHT IN A DOUBLE BIND. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Santi WE Soekanto \par \uc2 1,014 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 January 1995\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1995 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Businessman Abu Hasan entered the recent Nahdlatul Ulama (NU) congress a virtual unknown, emerged as a strong contender and left as a political hot-potato most NU ulemas couldn't get rid of quickly enough. \par \par \uc2  His actions have earned him the wrath of NU kyais (scholars). Some of his supporters have deserted him and he's not exactly the apple of the government's eye as shown by a few officials' less than favorable comments. \par \par \uc2  However, he should be at least remembered as the first person to break the NU's strong tradition of devotion toward leaders who are descendants of NU founder Hasjim Asj'ari, Abdurrahman Wahid's grandfather. \par \par \uc2  Abu managed to divide the loyalty of NU followers which, for the previous two terms, had been directed toward Abdurrahman alone. \par \par \uc2  The member of the People's Consultative Assembly from the ruling Golkar faction was so confident he would win, he invited journalists to his hotel room and handed out his curriculum vitae a day before the elections. \par \par \uc2  He got 136 votes to Abdurrahman's 157 votes in the preliminary election process. In the final vote, he allowed Abdurrahman to win by only a slim margin; he snatched 142 votes, while Abdurrahman won with 174 votes. \par \par \uc2  He's not as sore a loser as people have charged. \par \par \uc2  Immediately after his defeat, he told the press that Abdurrahman, more popularly known as Gus Dur, was indeed the better man. \par \par \uc2  He also expressed the hope that Gus Dur would establish an executive board which reflected the vote distribution - meaning he should get the second top seat. \par \par \uc2  Gus Dur excluded Abu Hasan from the board, backing his rejection with the charge that Abu Hasan was involved in afinancial scandal. \par \par \uc2  The businessman retaliated immediately. He threatened to sue Gus Dur for slander, and to expose various defects in the congress, held in Tasikmalaya, West Java, on Dec. 1 - 5. \par \par \uc2  He went so far as establishing an extra-structural body which named him as chairman and put former NU chairman and vice prime minister K.H. Idham Chalid in the advisory council. \par \par \uc2  He brought the internal NU conflict to a new height last week. \par \par \uc2  He assembled a number of fellow dissenters in one of his large houses in Jakarta to prepare for a repeat congress. He called the body the Coordinating Board for the Executives Board of NU (KPPNU) and modeled it on the official executive board. \par \par \uc2  Most of the prominent ulemas he named to the body, however, immediately declared that they didn't have anything to do with their appointments. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  Many ulemas, who silently resent Gus Dur's high-profile political activities but can't risk being associated with Abu Hasan, are \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  One prominent NU kyai (scholar) from the Jakarta chapter embodies this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  perfectly. He showed up to the first meeting of Abu Hasan's board because his name was on the membership list. He paced uncertainly in front of Abu Hasan's house, cellular telephone in hand, whispered with several journalists, then, having made up his mind, rushed to get away from the house. \par \par \uc2  Inside, Abu Hasan confidently told reporters that this kyai would eventually come, that he was delayed in heavy traffic. \par \par \uc2  Donors \par \par \uc2  For many NU members, who believe that the organization's leadership has been dominated by kyais from Java, the man who was born in Jambi province represented an alternative leader. \par \par \uc2  This explains why he received so many votes, especially from chapters outside Java. He has spread his roots deeply enough within the organization. \par \par \uc2  He is also very generous to NU. Abu Hasan has always donated large amounts for the organization's activities. \par \par \uc2  He was an important figure in the congress committee, and was assigned to explain to reporters that the organization will pay greater attention to social-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs. \par \par \uc2  This was Abu Hasan's turf. The successful telecommunication businessman clearly represented something that many participants believed to be practical solution to the problems of poverty facing many NU supporters in rural areas. \par \par \uc2  Abu told reporters that NU should implement professional and practical \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs in the next five years. "Most NU followers live in villages, so the logical programs would be simple upstream industry, especially agriculture," he explained. "Later on, we can go on toward other industries." \par \par \uc2  Abu was sure that the concept would work out fine if NU could cooperate with the government, something which wouldn't be difficult for person who is more a businessman than an ulema. \par \par \uc2  He has yet to show any sign of giving up his concepts in his defeat. "I love NU," he said when installing the extra-structural body. "The KPPNU will go on with its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs for the sake of improving the welfare of NU followers." \par \par \uc2  Born in 1934 in Kerinci, Sungai Penuh, Jambi, Abu Hasan became chairman of Ansor Youth, an organization of students under NU, in the West Sumatra province during his high-school years. According to Gatra weekly, he went on to study at the University of Gadjah Mada in Yogyakarta. \par \par \uc2  Upon graduating, he returned to work in Jambi. Between 1958 and 1960, he was chosen by Idham Chalid, then vice prime minister, to study abroad and represent the Ansor organization. \par \par \uc2  "I will never forget what Pak Idham did for me," he said of the respected NU scholar who still strongly supports him. "He gave me my opportunities." \par \par \uc2  Abu began his studies at the University of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania in 1960, and received a masters degree in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration in 1962. He worked for about a year in London, two years in Hong Kong and then spent some time in various jobs and places. He returned home in 1973. \par \par \uc2  Abu reportedly has a number of companies involved in various industries and in cooperation with various overseas projects. His wealth probably contributed to the widespread accusations of his buying votes. \par \par \uc2  He denies the vote buying accusations, challenging his opponents to prove it. So far, nobody has ventured to do so. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1995 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011103dr120058r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
