\par\par \b \uc2  SALARY RISE WELCOMED WITH SKEPTICISM. \b0\par\par\uc2 693 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 January 1995\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1995 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Legislators welcome the government's plan to increase the salary of civil servants and members of the Armed Forces (ABRI) but doubt if it would significantly improve their well-being. \par \par \uc2  But members of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  hoped that the salary rise would encourage civil servants and ABRI members to improve their services. \par \par \uc2  The salary rise was announced by President Soeharto yesterday when presenting the 1995/96 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan to the House, in which he said that limited state financial resources made the government raise the salaries modestly. \par \par \uc2  "The government has decided to raise the salary of civil servants, members of the Armed Forces, pensioned civil servants and retired soldiers and their widows by 10 percent," he said, followed by a thunderous applause - the only time it was heard throughout his speech. \par \par \uc2  The increase, Soeharto said, would be carried out in two stages: the salary rise of civil servants of Class I and II (the lowest echelons) will come into effect as of this month and those of Classes III and IV as of April. \par \par \uc2  The last time civil servants saw their salaries go up was in 1993, when the salaries of lower echelons went up by 18 percent and higher echelons by 12 percent. \par \par \uc2  "We have to thank the government for their initiative, even if the raise is only 10 percent," said Oka Mahendra from House Commission II overseeing home affairs. \par \par \uc2  Although Oka was convinced the increase could help minimize corruption and illegal fees, he pointed out that the government has yet to improve aspects other than salary, such as improving supervision, to make a significant change in the level of their productivity. \par \par \uc2  Soerjadi, the deputy House Speaker in charge of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  matters, said the planned salary rise would mean "very little" to the improvement of civil servants' and ABRI members' well-being, since inflation was already as high as 9.24 percent this year. \par \par \uc2  He hoped that the pay rise would help materialize a clean and respectable government that the people yearn for. \par \par \uc2  "But it's \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  secret that corrupt officials are usually those with a senior position, not lower-ranking bureaucrats who have no chance to embezzle state money," he said. \par \par \uc2  Inflation \par \par \uc2  Bambang Warih Kusuma from the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  commission said the increase was only made to conform with the level of inflation. \par \par \uc2  He pointed out that it would be more effective to transfer part of civil servants to the private sector. "By cutting down the number of civil servants and transferring them to private companies, they could work twice as effectively as they do now," he added. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the House's United Development Party (PPP) faction Hamzah Haz said the rise "would at least maintain the purchasing power of civil servants" and be a positive boost to the business sector. "They certainly won't be saving all their earnings," he said. \par \par \uc2  Aisyah Aminy, chairperson of House Commission I overseeing information, diplomacy and security, also voiced similar skepticism about the actual value of the salary rise. \par \par \uc2  "What does 10 percent mean if inflation is already nine percent?" asked the legislator from the Moslem-oriented PPP. \par \par \uc2  Outspoken legislator Aberson Marle Sihaloho from the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  commission, said that the government should be more serious about improving civil servants' welfare if it was serious about creating a clean and respectable government. \par \par \uc2  He said, what had often been heard from the government was its calls for austerity measures to save state money to keep development programs going. "It's just lip service," said the House member from the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI). \par \par \uc2  Economist Hadi Soesastro, from the Center for Strategic and International Studies, on one hand welcomed the salary increase, while on the other hand was \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  about its capability to minimize corruption, encourage productivity and increase efficiency. \par \par \uc2  "I'm afraid the connection between salary and quality of work from our civil servants is not that straight forward," he said. \par \par \uc2  He considered that the number of bureaucrats and their role in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was still too large and therefore continually became a burden to the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .(rid/hdj/pwn/pan) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1995 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011103dr16005ft\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
