\par\par \b \uc2  BI CALM ABOUT YEN SURGE. \b0\par\par\uc2 698 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 March 1995\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1995 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor J. Soedradjad Djiwandono said yesterday that the yen's surge would not have an adverse impact on the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , even though nearly 40 percent of the country's external debts is denominated in the Japanese currency. \par \par \uc2  "The government has acknowledged several times that any increase in the yen rate will have a potentially negative effect on the country's outstanding debts. But the real impact is not as big as feared by some analysts," the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's governor told a press briefing. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad said that the surge in the value of the yen or any other major currency could theoretically affect the country's foreign loans. The real impact of the appreciation on the debt service burden, however, depends on the rates effective during the repayment period. \par \par \uc2  "From that standpoint, the people should not have been shocked by the yen's appreciation over the last few days. The real impact will be felt only during the loan repayment period," he said. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad cautioned that simply calculating the impact of the yen's surge into the total value of the country's loans is not accurate since the rate of the yen is constantly fluctuating. \par \par \uc2  "Moreover," he stressed, "the loan repayment of the foreign debts is made on a year-to-year basis." \par \par \uc2  The dollar tumbled below the psychologically important 90-yen level to its post-war low of 89.65 yen and 1.3690 marks in Tokyo Wednesday before climbing back to 90 and 91 in the last two days. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad admitted that the yen's surge had fueled a dollar rush in the local money market mid-week as fund managers and other speculators tried to benefit from the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  was forced to intervene into the market by selling the dollar to stabilize the rupiah," he added. \par \par \uc2  On Wednesday several speculators dumped their rupiah and bought the greenback on worries that the yen's surge might hurt the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Earlier in January, the local money market was also feeling the pressure as fund managers dumped their rupiah in the wake of the Mexican financial crisis. Speculators feared that a similar crisis would also take place in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  governor blamed the fresh dollar rush on the speculative trading of foreign fund managers. \par \par \uc2  "The people seemed shocked. It was as if the surge in the yen's value was the end of the day. It's not right," he said of the people's jitters. \par \par \uc2  Besides, he added, most of the country's external debts are based on long-term contracts and their service and installment payments are made on an annual basis. \par \par \uc2  "So there is no reason to worry about the appreciation of yen. In fact, it is now stabilizing," he said. \par \par \uc2  According to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  governor, any analysis should be based on the government's ability to service and install its debts this year. \par \par \uc2  "From this standpoint, the position of our foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  are safe, more than enough to cover five months of imports," he added. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad said that around 35 percent of the US$12.97 billion foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  held by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is kept in Japanese yen accounts. \par \par \uc2  The proportion of yen holdings in the total international \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  is comfortable enough to service and install the yen-denominated debts," he said. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad added that the percentage of yen in the \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be increased to anticipate a future surge in the yen. \par \par \uc2  Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad announced recently that the country's outstanding debts totaled $87.6 billion as of last December, of which $58.6 billion were owed by the government, $24 billion by private borrowers and $5 billion by state companies. \par \par \uc2  The government allocated around Rp 17.65 trillion ($8.2 billion) of the 1994-1995 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for debt servicing and installments and another Rp 17.89 trillion ($8.32 billion) from the 1995-1996 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Debt servicing and installments account for around 23 percent of the Rp 78.02 trillion in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  projected in the next \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year, which begins next month. (hen) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1995 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011103dr3b006du\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
