\par\par \b \uc2  RI TO KEEP  \highlight22\uc2 FISCAL POLICY \highlight\uc2  PRUDENT. \b0\par\par\uc2 716 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 March 1995\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1995 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): President Soeharto assured a visiting World Bank delegation yesterday that Indonesia would continue its sound \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management and would always be prudent in managing its foreign debts. \par \par \uc2  The President, according to Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad, made the remarks in response to a suggestion from the World Bank team that the Indonesian government step up its sound macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management in light of an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  international \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  climate. \par \par \uc2  "The World Bank acknowledges our prudent policies. However, judging from recent developments in the world's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and from the recent experiences of Mexico's financial crisis, the World Bank has asked us to step up our sound \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management even more," reported Mar'ie. \par \par \uc2  Mar'ie yesterday accompanied the World Bank team, led by the new Vice President for East Asia and the Pacific Region Russell Cheetham, in a meeting with President Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  Cheetham, who was the director of the World Bank's resident staff here in the 1980s, recently replaced Gautam Kaji. \par \par \uc2  President Soeharto, Mar'ie added, reassured Cheetham that Indonesia will continue managing its debts in a prudent manner by accepting only soft and semi-concessional loans of long-term maturities. \par \par \uc2  "But the President also told Mr. Cheetham that he'd like the World Bank and other multilateral agencies to consider the impact of the rising yen on Indonesia's debt burdens," Mar'ie said without elaborating on what Soeharto meant specifically. \par \par \uc2  Cheetham will coordinate and preside over the annual meeting of the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI), an organization of donor agencies and countries headed by the World Bank. \par \par \uc2  CGI is scheduled to meet again in Paris in July. \par \par \uc2  Soeharto also expressed his concern on Tuesday about the excessive yen appreciation to Peter Sullivan, the Asian Development Bank Vice President for the Far East. \par \par \uc2  Senior officials of the National Development Planning Board said Wednesday that the government is likely to review the financing of several development projects, including those of the strategic industries, due to the rising yen. \par \par \uc2  Cheetham said he was impressed with Indonesia's high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, which exceeded seven percent last year, and he hoped that the high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion would be maintained to enhance equity and alleviate poverty. \par \par \uc2  He said he and President Soeharto discussed the latest situation of the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the impact the recent financial crisis in Mexico has had on other countries. They also exchanged views as to what kind of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management could effectively cope with all that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Weak \par \par \uc2  Reports from Tokyo yesterday indicated that the dollar remains weak as investors sat on the sidelines waiting for a crucial Bundesbank meeting, which the market did not expect to result in a cut in German \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The spot dollar was quoted at 88.31-33 yen in late trading after moving between 88.16 yen and 88.47 yen, compared with 88.45-48 yen a day earlier and New York's late Wednesday quote of 88.43 yen. \par \par \uc2  Although Indonesia has never once rescheduled its debt since 1967, some analysts have expressed concerns about the rising Japanese currency because, they say, every time the yen goes up by one percent against the dollar, it adds $300 million or more to Indonesia's debts outstanding. \par \par \uc2  The Japanese government, the biggest provider of Indonesia's loans, already stated two weeks ago that it had no remedy for the growing debt burden that the yen's sharp rise has inflicted upon the recipients of its loans. \par \par \uc2  Official figures cite that Indonesia's foreign debts, most of which are long-term government loans, totaled around US$88 billion. About 40 percent of those loans is denominated in yen, with annual \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  of between two-and-a-half and three percent. \par \par \uc2  About 15 percent of the country's 1995-1996 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which commences next month, will be financed by foreign development loans. \par \par \uc2  Mar'ie said last week that the government planned to increase the proportion of yen in Indonesia's foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  (around $13 billion) from the present level of 35 percent. \par \par \uc2  The minister also said that the government would "try to lobby" multilateral agencies whose loans are sometimes partly yen-denominated, to denominate all their loans in U.S. dollars. (hdj) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1995 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011103dr3v007dz\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
