\par\par \b \uc2  GOVT URGES CAUTION ON  \highlight22\uc2 SPENDING \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 598 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 April 1995\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1995 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The local administrations of the country's 27 provinces simultaneously received their lists of development projects for the coming \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year over the weekend, together with a message from President Soeharto urging caution in light of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the world's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 1995-1996. \par \par \uc2  The President said the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  might continue for some years to come and that Indonesia had to anticipate its negative effects. \par \par \uc2  "In the coming years, we will still face a number of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  constraints such as the possible impact of drops of the world's major currencies against the Japanese yen," Soeharto said in a written message, read out during ceremonies marking the reception of the lists of development projects for 1995-1996. \par \par \uc2  The new lists marked the start of the implementation of the 1995-1996 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which entails a total \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 78.02 trillion (US$35.46 billion). \par \par \uc2  About Rp 47.24 trillion is earmarked for the government's routine \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , such as personnel \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while the remaining Rp 30.78 trillion is to be used for development projects which will be carried out by the provincial offices of government ministries. \par \par \uc2  The President said that, apart from facing the impact of the world's unstable money market, Indonesia might also confront more challenges in exporting its commodities in the wake of the increase in the number of competitors from among the developing countries. In addition, he said, Indonesia might face tougher competition in obtaining foreign aid. \par \par \uc2  "We, therefore, have to be very careful in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  state funds," he said. \par \par \uc2  East Timor \par \par \uc2  East Timor, the country's youngest province, receives a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of around Rp 166.81 billion for the 1995-1996 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. Rp 58.32 billion of its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is earmarked for projects to be carried out by the ministry of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  works, making it the largest recipient in the province. The smallest allocation goes to the ministry of forestry, which gets Rp 352.37 million. \par \par \uc2  Bali receives Rp 173.9 billion, of which Rp 75.5 billion is allocated to ministry of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  works projects, the largest recipient; Rp 34 billion to the ministry of culture and education; Rp 10.9 billion to the ministry of agriculture; and Rp 8.2 billion to the ministry of health. \par \par \uc2  Rp 297.5 billion of the national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is reserved for development projects in South Kalimantan. The largest recipient in that province is also the ministry of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  works, with abudget of Rp 90.8 billion. The ministry of culture and education is in second place, with a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 38.1 billion, while the ministry of mines and energy came in third, with a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 37.8 billion. \par \par \uc2  Rp 260 billion is to go towards new development projects in Central Kalimantan. \par \par \uc2  North Sulawesi receives Rp 217 billion, of which Rp 76 billion is earmarked for projects of the ministry of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  works; Rp 46 billion for the ministry of culture and education; and Rp 19 billion for the ministry of transmigration. \par \par \uc2  South Sulawesi will spend Rp 618.7 billion on its development projects; Central Sulawesi Rp 239.78 billion; Bengkulu Rp 163.9 billion; West Nusa Tenggara Rp 211.64 billion; Riau Rp 303.51 billion; Irian Jaya Rp 702.61 billion; West Java Rp 1.22 trillion; and Central Java Rp 1.1 trillion. \par \par \uc2  East Java receives Rp 2.2 trillion; Lampung Rp 249.77 billion; West Sumatra Rp 281.9 billion; and Jambi Rp 195.89 billion. (hen) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1995 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011103dr43007i5\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
