\par\par \b \uc2  NO WORRIES ABOUT DEBT - BI CHIEF. \b0\par\par\uc2 652 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 April 1995\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1995 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's Governor Soedradjad Djiwandono reassured foreign bankers yesterday that the country's international reserve holdings have been diversified to match its annual foreign liabilities. \par \par \uc2  "Therefore, there should not be any worries about our capability to service our foreign debts," Soedradjad told a business luncheon of the Association of Foreign Banks' Representatives here. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad acknowledged, though, that the yen's surge has had a significant impact on Indonesia's foreign debt stocks because around 40 percent of its foreign liabilities is in yen. \par \par \uc2  He said did not want to belittle the impact of the steep rise of the Japanese yen, notably against the American dollar, since early last month. \par \par \uc2  But in so far as Indonesia's foreign debt service burdens this year are concerned, the impact of the appreciating yen is rather small, he added. \par \par \uc2  The 1995-1996 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocates Rp 17,900 billion ($8 billion) for servicing the government's foreign debts. \par \par \uc2  He said the annual foreign debt service burdens are calculated at the beginning of every year. \par \par \uc2  "We already know far in advance how much we should repay in dollar or yen and other foreign currencies this year. And we have accordingly adjusted the composition of our foreign reserve holdings," Soedradjad added. \par \par \uc2  Increase \par \par \uc2  For example, he noted, 35 percent of Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  of about US$13.3 billion at present consists of yen. That is a marked increase from 27 percent in 1993. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad recounted analysts' estimates that every one percent rise in the yen's rate against the dollar raises the amount of Indonesian foreign debts outstanding by around $300 million. \par \par \uc2  He conceded that if Indonesia's total foreign debts, currently estimated at the equivalent of around $90 billion (including $24 billion in private sector's loans), were converted into dollars, their amount might have been very close to the $100 billion mark. \par \par \uc2  Analysts here estimate that the 16 percent rise in the yen's rate over the last six weeks alone has increased Indonesia's foreign debt stocks by at least $5.7 billion. \par \par \uc2  "But one should take into account that most of our foreign debts are long-term liabilities with maturities ranging from 15 to 20 years," Soedradjad argued. \par \par \uc2  During that long period of time, the total debt stocks may fluctuate according to developments in the yen's exchange rate, he said. \par \par \uc2  He admitted that in the longer term the rise in the debt stocks would increase Indonesia's debt service ratio against exports which is now estimated at 31 percent. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, he added, it has become more imperative now to further increase exports because "our capacity to repay our debts depends on our export capability." \par \par \uc2  Challenges \par \par \uc2  Earlier in his remarks at the meeting, Soedradjad described the challenges Indonesia has been facing as a result of the opening of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to international competition. \par \par \uc2  "On one hand, we are facing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the international financial and monetary condition," he said. \par \par \uc2  On the other, he added, Indonesia is encountering increasingly tough competition because almost all other countries have also been reforming their economies to become more efficient and competitive. \par \par \uc2  "Therefore, we have no other choice. We have to adjust to the reality all the time through deregulation measures and prudent macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management," Soedradjad added. \par \par \uc2  The government, he noted, must maintain a prudent \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary management as well. \par \par \uc2  "We have been pursuing a sound \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by requiring the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be balanced every year." \par \par \uc2  On the monetary side, the government has been working hard to maintain a sound balance of payments with a sustainable current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , realistic exchange rate and single-digit inflation. \par \par \uc2  These tasks, Soedradjad conceded, are not simple or easy, especially because the open \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makes Indonesia quite sensitive to the developments in the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  where \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the rule. (vin) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1995 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011103dr4d0077e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
