\par\par \b \uc2  SOEDRADJAD'S WARNING. \b0\par\par\uc2 533 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 October 1995\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1995 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The warning sounded last week by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (\b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) Governor Soedradjad Djiwandono about the tendency of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to overheat should get adequate responses from other government agencies and businesspeople before the external balance shows signs of crisis. True, the developments, as Soedradjad explained at a banking seminar, are not yet a sign of crisis but it is a definite warning signal. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad cautioned that rapidly expanding \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities have caused the monetary growth to exceed targets set by the monetary authority, to maintain stability, curb inflation and to reduce the pressures on the balance of payments. That has forced domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to remain high. \par \par \uc2  Even though the 6.8 percent cumulative inflation rate during the first nine months was lower than the 7.4 percent in the same period last year, and the June trade \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of US$205 million was reversed into a surplus of $362 million for July, the situation is still a cause of great concern. \par \par \uc2  First of all, the cumulative trade surplus for the first seven months of this year was much lower than that in the corresponding period last year, due to the very high growth (29 percent) of imports. \par \par \uc2  The sharp increase in imports, partly caused by the robust pace of new investments, has been causing greater pressure on the balance of payments. Soedradjad acknowledged that the current account (balance of commodity and service trade) in the balance of payments may end up with a much larger \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  than last year's US$3.1 billion. Some analysts even forecast the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to reach as much as $8 billion, or six percent of the gross domestic product. That is much higher than the 2.5 percent target set by the government as a sustainable level. \par \par \uc2  The impact of the upward trend in the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  can still be contained by the high pace of capital inflows, both through foreign direct investment and portfolio capital. Heavy dependence on portfolio investments, which are highly speculative in nature, makes the country highly vulnerable to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has often been the main hallmark of the international financial market of late. Jittery investors could suddenly withdraw their capital simply because of wild rumors, which have nothing to do with the fundamentals of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  That is why, we feel, export promotion becomes even more imperative and that calls should be made for concerted efforts to remove high cost components in the production and trading sectors. This suggestion sounds like the same song over again, especially because a great portion of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has, of late, been spurred by the domestic market demand. However cliche may be the suggestion, the warning is loud and clear. \par \par \uc2  The dependence on portfolio capital, to cushion the impact of the widening current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , also makes it more imperative for the government to remain consistent with the spirit of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and bureaucratic reform and to continue deregulation packages. Inconsistencies, however short term they may be, would provide the wrong signal to investors, which would cause double blows: Stopping, or sharply reducing capital inflows and setting off capital flight. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1995 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011103drau004fx\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
