\par\par \b \uc2  ISLAM AND WESTERN CIVILIZATION. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Imam B. Prasudjo \par \uc2 1,266 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 December 1995\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1995 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  RHODE ISLAND, U.S. (JP): Over the last decades a number of analysts and commentators have discussed the transformation of human civilization. One of the best known ideas in Western social sciences is the modernization thesis: Every society is presumed to develop from an agricultural to an industrial society, from traditional to modern. The notion of industrialization has become central to our interpretation of global social processes. \par \par \uc2  The thesis is founded on the idea that the development of Western societies represents a universal evolutionary model of human history - that the hegemony of Western civilization has an inevitable impact on other parts of the world. The influence of the West is the driving force of modernization. With internationalization, the specific history of Western civilization is superimposed on other nations as "the history of human civilization in general" (Smart 1992). \par \par \uc2  Recent historical processes have led defenders of the Western alliance to the conclusion that Euro-America has emerged as the winner of ideological as well as cultural struggles. The defeat of fascism, absolutism and recently, communism, for example - Frances Fukuyama (1989) - confidently affirms the glorious victory of Western cultural domination. He considers this victory to be "the end of history". \par \par \uc2  While Fukuyama confidently proclaims the glorious victory of Western civilization, we do see the overwhelming influence of the West in all parts of world. Nonetheless, we can also see the unmistakable signs of a powerful counter trend. Religious resurgence, particularly among Moslems, stands as one of the most formidable barriers to the presumed victory of Western culture. \par \par \uc2  By the late 1970s and early 1980s, there was convincing evidence that these new religious movements had spread worldwide. The powerful influence of Islam has led to social, political, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and cultural changes in countries as diverse as Palestine, Saudi Arabia, Libya, Turkey, India, Pakistan, Malaysia, and Indonesia. What accounts for this religious resurgence? \par \par \uc2  Psychological \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been suggested as a major cause of religious revival. Western sociologist Bellah asserts that contact with the secular Western world has created an identity crisis within each individual Moslem. The questions "Who am I? What are my roots? and Who am I going to be?" have ignited a search for Islamic identities and values. \par \par \uc2  Undoubtedly, the impact of political, cultural and intellectual freedom gained after independent identity are significant contributions. The rigorous intensity of the search for Islamic values have become evident. The wave of religious enthusiasm, for example, has clearly influenced the activities of Indonesian students who study in many foreign universities. \par \par \uc2  Graduate and undergraduate students of mostly santri background (the inclined Islamic family) initiated the establishment of Islamic informal discussion groups on many campuses. Since 1989, taking advantage of new communication technology, the Indonesian Islamic computer network of about 400 to 500 members was established. Most of its members are Indonesian students who study in America, Europe or Australia. Islam is discussed in an effort to find solutions to the various problems facing the modern world. \par \par \uc2  Since religious enthusiasm has become more evident throughout the Moslem world, Samuel Huntington goes even further, suggesting that our future civilization will be dominated by conflict between Islam and the West. \par \par \uc2  This interaction of Islamic and Western influence is undoubtedly the cause of some cultural turbulence. Within societies and within individuals, we can identify several contrasting patterns of behavior: a radical opposition to Western cultural influence; a complete surrender to Western values; or aselective adaptation to modern conditions while maintaining the fundamental principles of Islam. \par \par \uc2  The adaptive responses of committed Moslems, for example, are grounded primarily in religious teachings. There are at least two primary responses to the conflict of religious and secular values. The first of these is "scripturalism" - the process of searching Islamic history for indigenous roots. The second is reinterpretation - the reinterpretation of Islamic teachings in the belief that many aspects of modernity are compatible with the underlying spirit of Koranic doctrines. \par \par \uc2  Undoubtedly, there has been a massive Islamic cultural movement in reaction to Western beliefs. In response to the globalization of Western culture, we can see a corresponding Islamization. New terms - Islamic State, Islamic Banking, Islamic Management System, Islamic Knowledge and Islamic Technology, for example - have become common in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  discourse among Moslems. \par \par \uc2  Nonetheless, this reactionary movement has yet to create auniformity of belief among Moslems. While we witness certain similarities in the views of Moslems worldwide, we can also see signs of diversity in the Islamic response to Westernization. Individual Moslems and groups, each with a particular cultural or national background, respond in different and sometimes contradictory ways. This pluralism can be seen in the diversity of Islamic religious teachings, for example. Nonetheless, during this first stage of change, common concerns and goals unite all Moslems, it rises above individual and local diversities in religious response. \par \par \uc2  The first stage created a mass society that reflected and required mass cultural production, chiefly as influenced by Western cultural values. The predominant cultural response of the Islamic world is also characterized by cultural pervasiveness and uniformity. \par \par \uc2  In the 21st century we enter the second stage of change, in which mass production is replaced by heterogeneous, diversified \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sociocultural forms. Centralized government has proven to be less effective than expected. Large corporations and organizations are breaking up into confederations of smaller companies. Mass production has given way to flexible production and just-in-time delivery. \par \par \uc2  The first stage was dominated by the interplay of two universal trends - Westernization and Islamization. In the second stage, this conflict declines in importance as mass response gives way to diversity. \par \par \uc2  While the doctrine of universal Islamic teaching was used to mobilize a cultural movement against mass Western cultural production, this opposition of Westernization and Islamization may not be appropriate for future diversified \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and cultural development. \par \par \uc2  In fact, in recent years stark differences of Islamic practice have become more apparent as a result of diverse interpretations of Islamic teaching. Thus, we witness differences in the Islamic practices of Moslems who live in different cultural regions; Moslems in Indonesia, Malaysia, Pakistan, Turkey, Iran, Iraq and other nations have each developed their own Islamic identity in response to local cultural needs. \par \par \uc2  To prepare for the 21 century, it is unnecessary to prepare for a cultural war against the West. The hegemony of Western culture will end without Islamic intervention, since Western nations are already surrendering much of their exclusive dominance in world affairs. In fact, the industrialized nations are increasingly receptive to cultural intrusions from other regions. At the same time, efforts to achieve global Islamization and cultural uniformity among Moslems may be ineffective, even detrimental to the development of distinct Islamic national and local cultures. \par \par \uc2  If current trends continue, the 21st century will be a time of great complexity and cultural diversity - whether we like it or not. Under these conditions, the development of Islamic religious tolerance will be more fruitful than the maintenance of inflexible or universalist doctrines. \par \par \uc2  Indeed, religious and cultural intolerance will burden those societies which cannot adapt. On the other hand, we may gain new strength by drawing on our rich cultural and intellectual inheritance that stem from orthodox Islam. \par \par \uc2  Those countries with tolerant, diverse societies - Malaysia and Indonesia, for example - have already begun to reap the cultural benefits of the second stage of change. Ideally, the diversity of the Islamic local traditions among Moslems will provide a strong foundation for the development of a tolerant and successful Islamic society in the coming years. \par \par \uc2  The writer is a Ph.D candidate in sociology at Brown University, Providence, Rhode Island, U.S.A. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1995 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011103drcb000k1\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
