\par\par \b \uc2  'ANTI-COMPETITIVE' POLICIES CAUSE MARKET DISTORTIONS. \b0\par\par\uc2 502 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 January 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Emil Salim, a former cabinet minister, yesterday criticized the government's "uncompetitive" \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies which help create market distortions. \par \par \uc2  Speaking at a two-day workshop, hosted by the Investment Coordinating Board, Emil noted that such uncompetitive policies conflict with the country's commitment to free trade arrangements in the Southeast Asian and Asia-Pacific regions. \par \par \uc2  Such uncompetitive policies, Emil said, include pricing policies on a number of commodities, tolerance toward cartel-like institutions, barriers of entry into a number of businesses and exclusive licensing. \par \par \uc2  "In Indonesia, cartels are not regulated but tolerated," Emil said. "The government even lets some associations help regulate businesses." \par \par \uc2  Because of the privileges, becoming executives at a number of associations, including the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) and the Associations of Indonesian Young Businesspeople (Hipmi), is the best deal to do business, Emil said. \par \par \uc2  "Therefore, it's not surprising many people compete for the chairmanship of Kadin or Hipmi. There is something behind it," he said. \par \par \uc2  He suggested that the involvement of associations in regulating business life be abolished because this can create barriers to entry into business. \par \par \uc2  He also questioned "obligatory" fees imposed by associations on their members. \par \par \uc2  Such levies, combined with various levies imposed by the government and local administrations, reduce the competitiveness of Indonesia's products both in local and international markets. \par \par \uc2  Emil questioned the need for such uncompetitive policies which help discourage exports at a time when the competitiveness of Indonesia's exports is weakening. \par \par \uc2  The policies include the banning of exports on certain commodities, supervision on the exportation of certain commodities, licensing of exporters and export \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  These uncompetitive policies, which are essentially protectionist, should be abandoned in the current era of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  liberalization, Emil said. \par \par \uc2  "Such policies were valid for the last 25 years, but not anymore, not for now and the coming years. Particularly since we will have free trade in Southeast Asia by 2003. Those policies are just irrelevant," Emil said. \par \par \uc2  In addition to the uncompetitive policies, Emil said Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is also plagued by the ineffectiveness of the law enforcement, which results in \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  In terms of "predictability in business", Indonesia is placed at the lowest among the seven members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), just above Vietnam, Emil said. \par \par \uc2  Besides Indonesia and Vietnam, ASEAN also groups Brunei, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand. \par \par \uc2  To make doing businesses in Indonesia more predictable, the government should launch more reforms on its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  legislations, some of which are still based on colonial rules. \par \par \uc2  "Our legal infrastructure for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially for the services sector, is still inadequate. We should floor the gas pedal, and reform it," he said. \par \par \uc2  Emil served as state minister of administrative reforms from 1971 to 1973, as minister of transportation from 1973 to 1978, as state minister of development supervision and e