\par\par \b \uc2  TRAFFIC JAMS, CONSTRUCTION PROJECTS DESTROY PUNCAK. \b0\par\par\uc2 515 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 March 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  7 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Text by Lela E. Madjiah photos by Arief Hidayat \par \par \uc2  PUNCAK, West Java (JP): The sun is nestling among the rows of houses down in the valley. Once in a while clusters of white clouds float with the gentle breeze across the growing fireball. \par \par \uc2  The sun quickly disappears, it is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  which house it is hiding behind. \par \par \uc2  The valley turns gray, the silhouettes eventually enveloped by darkness. The mist thickens as the night air becomes colder. It's time to head into the cottage and enjoy the barbecued corn. \par \par \uc2  Only the sound of water rushing down a stream breaks the still of the night. Nocturnal birds casually call, like a pair of cymbals underlying the regular rhythm of an orchestra. Peace and tranquility engulf all beings. \par \par \uc2  Puncak's beauty and relative serenity is what draws Jakartans on the weekend. Hordes of urbanites brave bumper-to-bumper traffic and long lines at the Taman Mini and Ciawi toll gates to briefly enjoy inhaling fresh, cool mountain air and feast on Puncak's soothing greenery. \par \par \uc2  Congestion along the road leading to Puncak was already bad by the 1970s. \par \par \uc2  "Why bother getting there at all? For fresh air? For which we choke on polluted air during the slow ride?" a university student said in 1977. \par \par \uc2  The traffic is now much worse. According to a recent police estimate, between 50,000 and 60,000 cars head for Puncak every weekend. On weekdays it falls to 10,000 vehicles. \par \par \uc2  As Jakartans became more wealthy in the mid 1970s, more people were able to make the short trip to get out of the city. Puncak has changed since then. \par \par \uc2  During Dutch colonial times, only the Dutch and a selected few Indonesians could enjoy the luxury of \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  a weekend in the mountain resort. Even on weekends one could count the number of vehicles traveling the winding road that sneaks its way between lush paddy fields, glowing orchards and neat tea plantations. After the country's independence, more individuals and companies started to buy property in the area. A number of inexpensive hotels were also developed to accommodate those not rich enough to build their own hideaways. \par \par \uc2  As the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew, many of the city's wealthy no longer felt satisfied merely \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  the weekend in a hotel or a rented villa. Owning a villa in Puncak was an image boost. A building rush ensued, without consideration of the consequences. \par \par \uc2  Now, most of the paddy fields and orchards have been replaced by buildings, many built on steep hills. \par \par \uc2  The development has brought dubious prosperity to the cash-strapped locals. The feel of money and the knowledge of what it might bring was too hard for them to resist, although it meant selling land that had been in the family for generations. Farmers who once ruled the land are now villa watchmen, their wives working as cooks or servants for the villa's owners. Many of their children, with no more land to till, work as ojek motorcycle drivers. \par \par \uc2  Who's to blame? \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018ds3h0084e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
