\par\par \b \uc2  SALOMON GROUP UPBEAT ABOUT RI'S POST-POLL  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 574 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 May 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): A foreign economist believes that Indonesia will stay with its pragmatic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies beyond next year's general election to maintain its impressive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance. \par \par \uc2  John P. Lipsky, chief economist at New York-based Salomon Brothers Inc., acknowledged here yesterday that all general elections create \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as do most situations that could lead to a change in \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Obviously the Indonesian situation is potentially a unique case because of its long-term stability," Lipsky told a seminar on the international financial market at the Financial Club. \par \par \uc2  He acknowledged that Indonesia's current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, in broad terms, are stable and consistent and have produced good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  results. \par \par \uc2  "If they continue to produce good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  results, it will enhance the likelihood that those policies will be preserved. So that strikes me as an important issue for the next few years," Lipsky said. \par \par \uc2  When asked if he was worried about inconsistent government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Lipsky said that \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability is a typical concern in all countries. \par \par \uc2  He noted that the strong performance of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be the result of policies that "now appear to be quite successful". \par \par \uc2  There has been a consistent direction in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, ones that evolve, are relatively stable and predictable, oriented toward liberalization and privatization and increasingly market orientated, Lipsky said. \par \par \uc2  If that continues, he added, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow robustly. \par \par \uc2  Growth \par \par \uc2  Salomon Brothers has predicted that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will remain high, at 8 percent this year and 8.5 percent next year. \par \par \uc2  Unlike Japan or the United States, where a rapid gain in productivity would require new technology and new breakthroughs, Indonesia can achieve productivity gains through the better allocation of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resources, the application and shifting of laborers to productive sectors as well as the creation of policies toward greater market orientation, Lipsky said. \par \par \uc2  "The better the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  does, the more likely we will see the willingness to maintain policies that have been successful." \par \par \uc2  He stressed that Indonesia needs to preserve its good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and maintain \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  consistency at a time when its current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is deepening. \par \par \uc2  When the government is successful in maintaining the stability of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and macroeconomic balance, Lipsky said, the deepening current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not be a problem for Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Salomon Brothers has projected that Indonesia this year will record a current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of US$9 billion, or 4.1 percent of the country's gross domestic product, higher than the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of $7.5 billion in 1995. \par \par \uc2  At this time, Lipsky said, Indonesia's current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  does not suggest any crisis as Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is relatively strong. \par \par \uc2  "We think that worries about the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia have been exaggerated," Lipsky said. "I think the deficits will be more manageable than many have suggested." \par \par \uc2  "What we are saying is that polices are not going to be a problem. If the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline becomes relaxed, the situation could change," he noted, adding that Indonesia depends very much on foreign capital to cover up its current account deficits. \par \par \uc2  He noted that Indonesia can easily tap foreign capital as long as the country can maintain its macroeconomic balance and the stability of policies. The availability of cross border investment and capital flows into the Asian region will continue to be extremely favorable in the coming years, he said. (rid) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018ds54009g7\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
