\par\par \b \uc2  REFORM OF THE FINANCIAL SECTOR. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,999 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 May 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following article is based on a paper presented by Dr. J. Soedradjad Djiwandono, the Governor of Bank of Indonesia in the 29th Asian Development Bank Annual Meeting Seminar on Financial Sector in Transition held on April 29, 1996 in Manila. This is the first of two articles. \par \par \uc2  MANILA: As we are aware, since the early 1970s, the external environment has been changing considerably, leading to increased \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and competition in world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Therefore, we have systematically tried to put in place all the essential elements that in the long-run would constitute the basis for a sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. It is for this reason that we have carried out thorough adjustments in all necessary areas with emphasis on particular aspects such as pricing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform, export promotion, financial sector reform, and many others. \par \par \uc2  Since the government usually has more than one target and expectation with different priorities, it is impossible to address them all with only one \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Accordingly, the adjustment policies adopted in Indonesia are combined as packages that address multi sectors that are related and compatible in nature. It is then necessary to arrange this long list of policies by phasing them according to their urgency based on careful consideration of underlying conditions. \par \par \uc2  In 1966, the New Order administration in Indonesia launched an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stabilization and rehabilitation program aimed at reducing inflation and ensuring sufficient supply of basic necessities. At the same time, the administration also reconstructed the infrastructure and carried out various efforts to support export capacity. Prior to the reign of the New Order, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition of Indonesia reflected the effects of a government preoccupied with political rather than \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues. \par \par \uc2  The performance of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was shown by the accelerating inflation rate that reached 635 percent in 1966 whereas the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  only registered an average of 2.8 percent growth per annum. In the external sector, imports continued to increase while in contrast, exports declined so that the depletion of foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  was irrevocable. \par \par \uc2  The liberalization pioneered by the New Order and carried out in stages, was prompted by changes in internal conditions as well as external factors. The first stage of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform (1970s) was part of the new initiatives of the New Order government in the implementation of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stabilization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by adopting a balanced \b \highlight22\uc2 budget policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , opening up the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for foreign and domestic investment activities and eliminating foreign exchange controls. \par \par \uc2  Deliberate campaigns were launched to move to development plans with the introduction of the Five Year Development Plans (Repelita), which started in \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year 1969/70 and ended in 1973/74. We call the entire five periods of Repelita that lasted up to 1993/94 as the Long Term Plan phase one, and starting 1994/95, we are heading toward the second phase. \par \par \uc2  In the 1970s and early 1980s, our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was very dependent on oil revenue. In fact, the oil boom substantially influenced the rise in the GDP to an average of 8,9 percent per annum in the 1979-1981 period. This situation discouraged the government from pursuing deregulation policies. With world wide recession in the early 1980s, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth was somewhat restrained to 2.3 percent, while at the same time, the balance of payments was pressurized due to unfavorable international oil price. \par \par \uc2  The drop in oil price diminished the role of the government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector as the engine of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. As a result, the government had to reschedule large government projects. These factors have brought about the adverse impacts as reflected in the drastic decline in foreign exchange earnings and government revenues, which in turn contributed to lower imports and investments, leading to a slowdown in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  As noted earlier, structural adjustments in Indonesia cover all essential elements of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that encompass not only macroeconomic management, but also micro elements as well as sectoral elements. On the macro side, we have tried for over a quarter century, to impose the necessary discipline for a sound macroeconomic foundation. The goal was to reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  by maintaining macroeconomic stability. This comprised, firstly, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  with all the elements of government revenue and \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including steps to simplify the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system, reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and ensure efficient \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  in order to sustain a dynamic balanced \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and, secondly, prudent and consistent monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Basically, prudent monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  comprised aspects to safeguard price stability both in terms of domestic prices (inflation) as well as foreign currencies (exchange rates). It also encompassed efforts to manage a sustainable current account in the balance of payments, debt management and borrowing strategy, as well as the maintenance of sufficient foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  These two policies were carried out with respect to their responsibilities to provide a proper framework for a market-oriented \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , resulting in broader \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  efficiency. We have aimed over these years for a stable and sustainable non-inflationary growth. \par \par \uc2  The above measures must be accompanied by other measures of equal importance on the micro side. In micro sense, the measures were aimed at increasing the effectiveness and efficiency of various government units. For the government sector to be effective and efficient in supporting and promoting a conducive climate for the business community, improvements in human resources should be encouraged through training, education, supervision as well as institutional advancement. \par \par \uc2  Both macro and micro adjustment measures were crucial in facing rising competition and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; nevertheless they needed to be complemented by sectoral adjustments. Sectoral \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies can be differentiated into the real sector such as production (manufacturing, agriculture, etc.), the distribution sector (trade and services), and the financial and banking sector. \par \par \uc2  The goal of sectoral measures is to increase the effectiveness and efficiency, and hence the competitiveness, of all sectors in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including the financial sector. Its design was to eliminate the over-\b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  of our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by reducing government controls and relying more on market mechanism. Nonetheless, our destination is not a free market as government intervention is still feasible if conditions necessitate it. \par \par \uc2  We understand that the financial sector serves as an intermediary between depositors with a surplus of funds and investors who need those funds. On the other hand, Indonesia like other developing countries, is facing a gap between limited savings and increasing investment needs. Therefore, efforts to adjust the financial sector will enhance the strategic function of banks and other financial institutions to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development as the reforms in the financial sector constitute an integral part of the overall adjustments policies. \par \par \uc2  On the whole, adjustment policies in the financial sector reflected a consistent intention to achieve at least three basic objectives: \par \par \uc2  * to move toward a predominantly market-based financial system; \par \par \uc2  * to provide effective protection as needed by the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  so that they can benefit from the services offered by the financial system; and \par \par \uc2  * to build an efficient and strong financial system that will support stable and healthy \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  In the banking sector we began liberalization measures in June 1983, when the government announced its first serious deregulatory effort by allowing banks to determine their own deposit and lending rates. Interest rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was adjusted to rely more on market mechanism. \par \par \uc2  Formerly, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  of state banks for both deposits and loans were determined by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Since state banks held the largest market share (60 percent), all \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  were virtually determined by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . These regulated rates were often too low to encourage domestic savings. After June 1983, the determination of \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  were left to each bank's discretion, relying more on market forces, thereby becoming more attractive to depositors. Concurrently, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Certificates in 1984 and Money Market Securities in 1985, which were used as indirect monetary controls. \par \par \uc2  The process of liberalization in the financial sector was enhanced by the next measure in October 1988. The government unleased its most important deregulation package to date, one which fundamentally changed the face of Indonesian banking. \par \par \uc2  Pakto, as the package come to be known, removed the restrictions on new private banks which had been in effect since 1971. All limit on domestic bank branching were removed. Foreign banks were permitted to form joint ventures with local partners. The foreign partner could hold a maximum of 85 percent share and the new banks had a minimum paid-up capital requirement of $30 million. \par \par \uc2  Existing foreign banks in Jakarta were allowed to branch out to six major provincial cities. State-owned enterprises were given leave to place up to 50 percent of their deposits outside state banks. This gave private banks a glimpse of an enormous, previously off limits pool of deposits and, at the same time, forced state banks to compete for deposits. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  imposed legal lending limits which, among others, restricted a bank's aggregate amount of loans and advances to 20 percent of bank capital for any customer, and to 50 percent bank capital for any one group of companies with common ownership. These limits were designed not only to prevent banks from being overexposed to a limited client based but also to drive large business conglomerates to seek market based financing from a range of financial institutions. \par \par \uc2  Also, we have taken steps to liberalize the capital markets with the aim of creating and maintaining investor confidence and a conducive environment for investors. In December 1987 and December 1988, the government took steps to energize the capital market that had slumbered through a decade of existence. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  limiting daily price swings to 4 percent of the price of a stock was abolished and foreigners were allowed to buy some shares. Foreign security houses were also given the green light to form joint ventures with local partners, it is true, of course, that the sudden emergence of competition in 1989 from equity markets had a profound effect on how banks marketed themselves to customers. \par \par \uc2  The measures above have encouraged more advanced banking activities as indicated by many banking indicators, in terms of the number of banks as well as the value of fund mobilized and a loan extended. In line with the above development, we remained concerned about the importance of maintaining macroeconomic stability. Our long period of experience has shown that macro management is a necessary condition to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, we foresaw that steps to increase prudential measures are equally important and on January 1990, we further improved the credit system by streamlining liquidity credit to three priority areas: food procurement, cooperatives, and investment. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was aimed at lowering inflationary pressures and excess liquidity that may unfavorably affect savings mobilization, and to improve credit structure, remove distortions in market mechanism in the creation of market oriented \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , increase efficiency in the allocation of funds, promote the role of banks in managing, carrying out the national credit system, and enhance \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's role in monetary control. \par \par \uc2  Following prudential efforts to create a sound banking system, at the end of February 1981, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  introduced a new set of measures which included the introduction of capital adequacy requirements and encouraged banks to improve their management, strategy, and operational system. \par \par \uc2  Also, by the end of March 1992, the New Banking Act was introduced to provide a legal foundation for responsible banking management that included the rights and obligations of related parties. To enforce the new act, a series of government regulations were issued concerning the operation of commercial banks, rural credit banks, and profit sharing banks, so as to further strengthen efforts to promote sound banking, and to provide guidelines for their operation. \par \par \uc2  To assist banks to persist with prudential principles, on September 1994, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  updated the improved Net Open Position (NOP) regulations by easing the NOP limit for transaction up to 25 percent of bank capital, both for the balance sheet as well as the off-balance sheet transactions. \par \par \uc2  By doing this, banks are expected to have more leeway to make necessary adjustments in their open position. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document 