\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 FISCAL \highlight\uc2  DECENTRALIZATION. \b0\par\par\uc2 614 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 May 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  A seminar last week on the impact of local levies on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  concluded that most local administrations are ignorant of the need to implement probusiness policies because the central government still almost entirely holds the taxing power related to main \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities. The meeting also discovered just how dependent local administrations are on fundings from the central government due to the absence of fair rules on intergovernmental \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations. \par \par \uc2  The problem seems to have been exacerbated by the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  encountered by local administrations regarding their \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plans because the amount of funds transferred from the central government is set on an annual basis. \par \par \uc2  Provincial and district administrations have only a few months in which to plan their annual budgets, which are implemented on April 1, because the amount of their respective transfers from the central government are disclosed only after the national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is proposed to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the first week of January. \par \par \uc2  Local administrations, besides encountering \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  funding \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , have been under pressure to expand their budgets to meet the increasing demand of their local people. The result, as disclosed at the seminar, is the proliferation of local \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and user fees. There are now five local \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and 58 user fees collected by provincial administrations, and 36 \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and 134 user fees levied by district administrations. \par \par \uc2  However, the results of studies discussed at the seminar revealed that quite a number of those local \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and user fees are totally uneconomical, meaning that the costs of their administration and collection are much higher than the revenues collected. Still more shocking is the finding that the power to collect those \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and user fees is mostly abused to extort kickbacks. All this is obviously detrimental to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities, notably business development. Yet since the \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  authority is still controlled almost entirely by the central government, local administrations are unaware or indifferent to the need to stimulate private investment operations in their areas. \par \par \uc2  This attitude is strikingly different from that among local administrations in countries where the decision-making and taxing power, and the responsibilities for many \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  services and functions, have adequately been decentralized. \par \par \uc2  Local administrations with adequate administrative autonomy always pursue probusiness policies because they fully realize that investments stimulate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth which in turn creates jobs, generates purchasing power and consequently widens the base of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue sources and increases the opportunities for the collection of numerous user fees. \par \par \uc2  The problems described above show how imperative and urgent it is for the central government to speed up the development of local autonomy in districts. Decentralization should mean devolving both \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  responsibility and revenue sources. The one year implementation of the development of local autonomy in 26 districts, selected in early 1995 as pilot projects for administration decentralization throughout the country, shows how slow the process has been due to the great hesitation on the part of central ministries to transfer their responsibilities to district-level offices. The director general for regional autonomy, Sumitro Maskum, himself admitted last month that only six of the 50 steps in the process to full autonomy in the 26 districts had been completed. \par \par \uc2  The central government should display a stronger political will to accelerate the development of local autonomy. The experiences of other countries that have decentralized their administration systems have proven that decentralization of responsibility brings local accountability. Local officials with greater autonomy will have a greater stake in good governance since they can clearly be identified by taxpayers and voters as the architects of success or the cause of failure. Local accountability seems even more crucial for such a vast archipelagic state as Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018ds5t002sj\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
