\par\par \b \uc2  ANALYSTS PREDICT JSX TRADING TO REMAIN QUIET. \b0\par\par\uc2 938 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 August 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Several analysts are forecasting that trading activities on the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) will remain quiet this week due to the wait and see attitude of investors. \par \par \uc2  "I think the situation would be unchanged next week," a senior trader from PT Pentasena Arthasentosa, Sumirat, told The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  "Like this week, the market might lose support from both foreign and local investors," he added. \par \par \uc2  The president of PT Inter Pacific Securities, L.G. Rompas, noted that fundamentally, there is no reason for a weak performance on the JSX but there might be another reason for investors' wait and see attitude. \par \par \uc2  "Our macroeconomy and stock market structures are much better now, so we can see that, unlike in the past years, the market easily recovers following any big drops," Rompas told the Post over the weekend. \par \par \uc2  Rompas, however, said that most foreign fund managers might need more time to get a better understanding about Indonesia before deciding on whether to enlarge or to cut their investment here. \par \par \uc2  Sumirat also said that lack of fresh foreign funds will further discourage foreigners from making big deals. It means that they will continue to be sidelined because they really do not have buying power, rather than because of fundamental reasons. \par \par \uc2  "In such a situation, only big news, like those on much better than expected first-half earnings results, may ignite investors to bring in fresh funds." \par \par \uc2  Several big companies, like Indosat and Tambang Timah, have published their results in the first half of this year, which showed higher profits. Unfortunately, the higher profit figures were just in line with fund managers' expectation. \par \par \uc2  "No wonder the prices of the two companies' shares did not increase following the announcement of the results," a dealer with a foreign brokerage said. \par \par \uc2  Sumirat said that lack of buying power is also attributable to many rights issues which have raised the amount of fresh funds to more than Rp 2.5 trillion this year. \par \par \uc2  "It's worth noting that many big companies like Gajah Tunggal, Indah Kiat and Polysindo issued rights shares." \par \par \uc2  Commenting on the large amount of funds raised through a number of rights issues, Rompas said, "It means that our market is active despite the fact that new initial \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offerings are very limited this year, as compared to last year." \par \par \uc2  Rompas and Sumirat, however, didn't clearly mention the main reason for foreigners' hesitation to bring in more fresh funds. \par \par \uc2  Rompas only said: "Of course, investors also take a close look at noneconomic factors." \par \par \uc2  Profit taking \par \par \uc2  Profit taking on most blue chips pushed down stock prices on the JSX by 2.3 percent last week. \par \par \uc2  The JSX Composite Index closed at 547.71 points last week, down by 13 points, following a late rebound in the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Several dealers said that the decline might be affected by price drops in the region, while others said that domestic political issues were the main reason for such a decline. \par \par \uc2  Although the government has repeatedly mentioned that the July 27 mass riots had minimal impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , what was happening in the market signaled that the market is still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the country's political stability, a dealer said. \par \par \uc2  The fact that many foreign fund managers joined a capital market conference here last week has also been cited by several stock analysts, businessman and government official as proof that foreign investors are still positive about investing here. \par \par \uc2  Data from the JSX show that despite profit taking actions, foreign investors turned to be net buyers last week, as compared to a net selling position in the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Sell transactions by foreigners amounted to Rp 680 billion (US$288 million) against buy transaction of Rp 700 billion last week, as compared to the previous week's figures of Rp 1.03 trillion for selling transactions and Rp 903 billion for buying transactions. \par \par \uc2  Total transactions on the JSX were recorded at 587 million shares valued at Rp 1.2 trillion against the previous week's 650 million shares worth Rp 1.5 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Corporate action \par \par \uc2  Several counters of the Gajah Tunggal Group - BDNI, Gajah Surya Multi Finance, Andayani Megah and Gajah Tunggal - were actively traded last week due to reports on plans of acquisition and rights issuance. \par \par \uc2  The group's multifinance arm, Gajah Surya, topped the big gainers, with its share prices jumping by 40 percent to Rp 1,400 at last week's close on news that it will acquire a 51.8 percent stake in the group's commercial bank, BDNI. \par \par \uc2  BDNI recorded total transactions of 47 million shares worth Rp 90 billion while Gajah Surya made total transactions of 56 million shares valued at Rp 82 billion. \par \par \uc2  The group's tire cord maker Andayani booked total transactions of 21 million shares worth Rp 28 billion and its tire maker Gajah Tunggal, 29 million shares valued at Rp 35 billion. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Great River International, which is currently preparing the establishment of two joint ventures with Indomulti Inti of the Salim Group, enjoyed a trading volume of 30 million shares worth Rp 38 billion. \par \par \uc2  Great River's move also boosted the share price of its joint venture partner, Indomulti, to close 18 percent higher last week at Rp 1,900. \par \par \uc2  The top 10 stocks in values, other than BDNI, Gajah Surya, Great River and Gajah Tunggal, were Telkom (with a trading value of Rp 70 billion), HM Sampoerna (Rp 51 billion), Dharmala Intiland (Rp 40 billion), Bimantara Citra (Rp 37 billion), Semen Gresik (Rp 36 billion) and Gudang Garam (Rp 36 billion). (alo) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018ds8c004xw\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
