\par\par \b \uc2  GOVT URGED TO LIBERALIZE PALM OIL BUSINESS. \b0\par\par\uc2 579 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 August 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The government should liberalize the palm oil industry to prepare it to compete on the world market, analysts said yesterday. \par \par \uc2  "Oligopsony, oligopoly and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  are hampering the development of our palm oil industries. The government should liberalize it to create efficiency," Faisal H. Basri, an economist of University of Indonesia, told a seminar on crude palm oil business regulations. \par \par \uc2  The meeting, which was organized by the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance, and Intipesan Pariwara, was also addressed by economists and agronomists M. Nawir Messi, Bustanul Arifin, Didik J. Rachbini and Bungaran Saragih. \par \par \uc2  Faisal, the chairman of the Department of Economics and Development Studies at the university, noted that more than 70 percent of Indonesia's crude palm oil production is used by the cooking oil industry, which is controlled by the Salim Group and Sinar Mas Group. \par \par \uc2  The two groups have managed to control the prices. "They can keep the prices lower than those on the world market, while at the same time they can get a bigger margin from the increasing prices of cooking oil," he said. \par \par \uc2  He criticized the poor government policies on farm commodities, including on crude palm oil. "There is no uniform \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on our commodities. Every commodity is subject to separate regulations. But it is only the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on rice that has a strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundation," he said. \par \par \uc2  Bustanul Arifin, a researcher of the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance, noted that there has not been any integration between the upstream and downstream industries of crude palm oil. \par \par \uc2  Faisal suggested that the crude palm oil industry be liberalized by abolishing the export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of between 40 percent and 60 percent on crude palm oil as it is not effective. "To make our crude palm oil products competitive, the government should abolish the export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. \par \par \uc2  He added that the government should also scrap the import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  of about 20 percent on cooking oil to help create efficiency in local industries. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian government imposes export \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  to guarantee the supply of crude palm oil to cooking oil industries and import tariffs to protect the cooking oil industries. \par \par \uc2  According to M. Nawir Messi, the program director of the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance, in 1995 alone the export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused the loss of US$173 million in foreign exchange which could have been gained from exports. \par \par \uc2  The export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  has also caused a transfer of welfare worth $102 million from crude palm oil producers, including farmers, to the cooking oil producers because the local price control forced the producers to sell their crude palm oil below the normal market prices. \par \par \uc2  Bungaran Saragih, a noted agricultural expert of Bogor Agricultural University shared the analysts' view, saying that despite the bleak condition, the crude palm oil business is very promising on the world market. \par \par \uc2  "The crude palm oil business is very promising as the international demand for crude palm oil-based products has been increasing steadily," he said. \par \par \uc2  The demand for crude palm oil in Indonesia has increased an average of 16.4 percent per year, due mainly to the expanding downstream industries such as those which produce cooking oil, margarine, soap and other crude palm oil-based goods. \par \par \uc2  He noted that Indonesia is the second largest producer of crude palm oil after Malaysia with a total output of 4.5 million tons last year. (13) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018ds8f00480\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
