\par\par \b \uc2  MONETARY  \highlight22\uc2 POLICY \highlight\uc2  AND CAPITAL MARKET DEVELOPMENT. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,397 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 August 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following is an excerpt of a paper presented by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor J. Soedradjad Djiwandono at a conference held by the Capital Market Supervisory Board on Aug. 8, 1996. This is the first of two articles. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA: The Indonesian financial system has experienced a very dynamic time during the last few years. From the backward situation in the late sixties, the Indonesian financial system has been moving to the forefront of Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. In the process, the advancement of the financial system has contributed to the promotion of the private sector in the country; thus becoming a more powerful engine in stimulating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity. Successes and failures are a fact of life; likewise the growth of the financial system has been marked by successes and failures. However, from what we have witnessed, the Indonesian financial system has been moving forward in spite of the failures and problems and has indeed passed the test of time. \par \par \uc2  In the process of structural transformation, special efforts in the form of financial reforms, popularly dubbed "banking and financial deregulation" have been implemented for more than ten years to stimulate the financial system and meet the needs of an increasingly globalized \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Therefore, when the wind of globalization swept through the Indonesian system, the existing financial structure was able to adapt to the new situation and move along with the process of globalization. \par \par \uc2  As we are aware, in general the financial system is divided into direct and indirect systems. Over the last few decades the indirect financial system, especially the banking system, has led the way in meeting the needs for financial \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. This is a typical pattern that has emerged in other countries as well. In the process, banking reform has energized the financial system in Indonesia which now boasts 240 registered banks with total assets of more than US$ 165 billion. The proliferation of branches throughout Indonesia has enabled banking services to reach most people, even in remote places. This expansion has resulted in a multiplying of the amount of savings mobilized by the banking sector. \par \par \uc2  The rapid progress of the banking industry has contributed to the achievement of many other objectives. First, the development of the Indonesian private sector is very much related to the progress made by the Indonesian banking system. Almost like venture capitalists, the banks have successfully promoted Indonesian entrepreneurs from the bottom rung of the ladder in the 1960s to respectable prosperity in recent years. \par \par \uc2  Second, the private sector has increasingly become one of the important engines of Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development and it is evident that the banking system has played a major part in Indonesia's overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. This is reflected in the high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and the very dynamic expansion in many sectors. \par \par \uc2  Third, this process also explains the boost in the export sector in the last few years. Indeed the private sector is the most important contributor to government revenues. \par \par \uc2  All of these have helped build the capacity of the government to fulfill its obligations to foreign lenders. \par \par \uc2  In the last few years, however, the government has also made efforts to develop the direct financial system to mobilize resources for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . From the most recent developments we can now see that the direct financial system has been increasingly moving forward to make up for lost time. Led by rapid progress in the capital market, the direct financial system has also moved to the forefront of the development of private debt securities such as commercial papers, medium-term notes, and bonds as well as asset backed securities. \par \par \uc2  Non-banking financial institutions such as insurance and finance companies, venture capital firms and pension funds have grown in a very dynamic way to complement the raid growth of the banking system. These development received strong legal endorsement from the new banking and insurance law as well as the pension funds law enacted a few years ago. In this case, the capital will certainly contribute to the process by enhancing the existing legal structure and at the same time introduce new elements to our financial sector, such as the investment management industry which attracts a great deal of attention these days. \par \par \uc2  The advancement of capital markets is apparently a natural process of the venture capital nature of the banking system. The companies which have grown enormously with the help of the banking system have in recent years accumulated sufficient capacity to go \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and mobilize financial resources directly from the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We notice that the number of companies listed on national stock exchanges has grown to around 250. In addition, methods adopted by listed companies to raise financial resources are varied; including initial \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offerings, right issues, stock splits, stock dividends etc. \par \par \uc2  We can thus observe that the emergence of stock markets has enabled corporations to diversify not only their source of funds but also their savings portfolio. Those corporations have also had an opportunity to improve their capital structure through the betterment of their debt equity ratios, which in turn also benefited lending institutions, especially Indonesian banks. \par \par \uc2  The development of the capital market has several links with the monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  undertaken by the monetary authority. In a closed environment, monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could affect capital markets by changing the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  liquidity. \par \par \uc2  A rise in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  usually has a negative impact on capital markets because investors can choose to place their money either in the form of equities or fixed income stocks. However, as financial markets become more open such relations are becoming less clear. From studies conducted to identify the relations between \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and stock market indices in Indonesia, we can see that the relationship is not straightforward. This phenomenon is especially true since the surge of capital inflows to emerging markets started in 1993. \par \par \uc2  In fact, we can observe that there is a strong correlation between Indonesian stock market indices and other markets in this region. The co-movements of these indices are very much explained by what is happening in developed countries, particularly the United States. A major change of mood in the New York Stock Exchange will eventually bring changes to the stock exchanges in this region. Similarly, a change in the Fed Funds rate also has a great influence on this country's market. \par \par \uc2  More importantly, the development of capital markets will depend on macroeconomic conditions. Achieving the appropriate macro conditions is vital for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a whole. Macroeconomic stability will provide a strong foundation for continuous development. Furthermore, macroeconomic stability is an essential factor in building the confidence of investors and the business world. \par \par \uc2  Monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be aimed at maintaining macroeconomic stability. Of course, this \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be implemented prudently and consistently. Prudent monetary policies include ensuring that the value of the rupiah is not volatile in respect to maintaining stable prices of goods (management of the inflation rate), as well as ensuring that the value of the rupiah in terms of other currencies remains realistic. \par \par \uc2  To achieve these requires the administration of a sound balance of payments in terms of managing the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at a sustainable level, debt management and a sensible borrowing strategy, as well as the management of stable foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 . All these are to be conducted in a timely, well planned and calculated manner so as to constantly create certainties or reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  by encouraging stability in the framework of increasing the competitiveness of the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures which are drastic and shocking will be avoided. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, the Indonesian capital market also affects the monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  because of the capital market's significant degree of openness. This particular characteristic has made capital flows to and from the country increase significantly. At a time when the Indonesian market is attractive compared to other parts of the world, the inflows of capital create a strong pressure on Indonesian exchange rates and eventually on the level of money supply. The greater the capital inflows, the more money is being created. The same is true of the reverse process, namely that capital outflows will cause a strain on bank liquidity. The greater problem will arise if there is any sudden reverse process, such as a capital market crash due to the loss of confidence as was the case Mexico. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018ds8j004f8\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
