\par\par \b \uc2  A PERSPECTIVE ON ASIAN VALUES. \b0\par\par\uc2 2,057 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 August 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  This is the second of two articles based on an excerpt from a paper presented by Robert J. Hawke, former Australian prime minister, at the 19th anniversary conference of the Indonesian Capital Market on Aug. 8. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA: In the United States income inequality has worsened dramatically over the past 20 years and now stands at its worst levels since records have been kept. Among industrialized nations, America has the greatest division between rich and poor (and the greatest deterioration over the past two decades). While women's incomes have improved with the decline in discrimination, real wages for men are below the levels of the late 1960s. Inequality of family incomes, as measured by the Gini ratio, is the highest it has been since the U.S. Census Bureau began collecting that data in 1947. At the level of top incomes the picture is rosy. Business Week magazine reported recently that a CEO's wages and compensations are typically about 150 times those of the average worker in his company - in 1974 the comparable figure was about 35 times. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has exacerbated income inequality in the United States. In the decade of significant net \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  reductions between 1980 and 1990, the Gini ratio rose faster on an after-\b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  than on a pre-\b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  basis. \par \par \uc2  And when it comes to the sanctity of human life the United States does not speak from a position of strength. Every independent analyst has identified poor gun control laws in the U.S. as the principal cause of deaths from firearms in that country - 39,500 in 1994, an increase of 64 percent in less than thirty years. If American legislators had put the same fervor into standing up to their gun lobbies and putting sensible provisions on the statute books as they have done in preaching to Asians about human rights, scores of thousands of their murdered citizens would be alive today. The degree of terror felt in their daily lives by so many ordinary Americans simply because their government is not prepared to stare down the gun lobbies is no less real because it is incapable of measurement. This tyranny of terror in the greatest free enterprise society is an infringement of human rights. \par \par \uc2  These considerations do not escape the attention of East Asians when they are being lectured by the West. Similarly, they are perplexed when they look at the brutal record of European powers in Asia and the historical timetables in those nations, and the United States, in achieving some of the human rights that they demand should be introduced immediately in all the countries of East Asia. It is significant that this cynicism is not confined to the targets of the West's moral assaults but is shared throughout the region. \par \par \uc2  It behooves everyone who is genuinely interested in establishing a better international environment to understand this mind-set of the region which increasingly will hold the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  center stage. I recently summed up the position in this way. East Asians are not singing entirely in tune but they are, to a large extent, committed to the same song. It is a song with several verses. \par \par \uc2  First, your culture is not our culture, your history is not our history, your religions are not our religions. Second, by force of arms you ruthlessly appropriated our territories, our resources and imposed your rule upon us. Third, after more than a century and our own fair share of barbarism to others (some are more reluctant than others to admit this) we have learned the basic rules of success of your \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  system and are operating it much more efficiently than you. \par \par \uc2  Fourth, under that system you took more than a hundred years to establish within your own countries the political norms which you now demand that we introduce in a dramatically shorter time frame. Fifth, you point to the inadequacies within our societies, but we ask you to look at your own - do you suggest that your democracies currently present a shining example to the rest of the world? Sixth, while you should acknowledge that according to our value systems, as compared with yours, there is a different emphasis between the rights of individuals and the society as a whole, we recognize there is room for improvements in the area of human rights. \par \par \uc2  We believe that will come as we share the fruits of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth through rising living standards for our people - this is a fundamental human right and we are doing that better than you. Seventh, for all these reasons, don't think that you have the unilateral right to set the agenda; stop preaching to us and let us get on together with the business of constructive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  co-operation from which we all can benefit. \par \par \uc2  Now you don't have to love the song, but you can't ignore it. These attitudes are important in understanding the emerging international political environment. With an acute sense of past exploitation by non-Asian powers and a present sense of pride in their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  achievement, the countries of East Asia are not going to be dictated to by the West, and, in particular, they are not going to be dictated to on the question of "human rights". On this subject, according to definitions they regard as relevant, they assert that their record is superior to those who would lecture them. \par \par \uc2  None of what I have said implies that those of us who have enjoyed the opportunities and benefits of living in democracies should be indifferent to the absence or abuse of freedom elsewhere in the world. I believe my own record in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  life attests to my embrace of that principle. But the more I listen to the tirades from the West against the downside of Asian values and the neglect of human rights in the region the more I am depressed by the hypocrisy of so many proponents of this position. \par \par \uc2  It is part of the Confucian ethic that the great and the good lead by example. If the U.S. - the wealthiest nation on earth - were to be giving effective global leadership to help the poor and the oppressed, one would not expect that country to be leading the way among developed nations in cutting aid to poorer countries - to a point where, at 0.27 percent of national GDP, it is at the lowest proportion for 20 years. The U.S. now gives less aid than France; meanwhile, it adamantly continues its crippling impact on the work of the United Nations by refusing to meet its legitimate dues. \par \par \uc2  And when one hears complaints from U.S. business leaders and legislators about unacceptable labor standards in some Asian countries the image often emerges of the protectionist hiding under the cloak of the humanitarian. How hard have some of these protagonists of universal values spoken out against the further marginalization of the low-paid and under-privileged in their own country? \par \par \uc2  Neither political systems nor values in any society remain constant. In the United Kingdom the institutions of governance which reflected the power of property could not ultimately withstand the forces for change unleashed with the Industrial Revolution. Nor would anyone suggest that the Victorian values of the second half of the last, and the first part of this century - which resembled in many ways the so-called Asian values of today - reflect the current values of British society. \par \par \uc2  Just as inevitably, the values of Asia will not remain constant. As the habitat of its people moves increasingly from a rural to a city environment, the influence of extended family and of religion will diminish and values will change. Similarly, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and extension of the market will, over time, produce irresistible pressures for political liberalization. \par \par \uc2  Before bringing together the lessons to be drawn from these realities let me make two points. First, in much of the discussion about Asian values the term is often used as code words for "Chinese values". China for many has replaced the Soviet Union as the threat to global stability. Certainly China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has been spectacular since the first reform steps in 1978, averaging some 9 percent per annum. \par \par \uc2  The question is not if, but when, it will become in absolute terms the largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the world. This will happen some time in the first quarter of the next century - it will then be once more in the position it has occupied for most of the last two-and-a-half thousand years. I believe that fear of China is misplaced, both in terms of history and, currently, in light of the enormous demands upon its political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resources to meet the challenge of its own internal development. \par \par \uc2  Second, I have spent some time in criticism of the U.S. but we should never forget the debt we owe to that great country. Without its steadfastness against the threats of Soviet subversion and global domination the world could have been facing an infinitely bleaker future than it does today. Having delivered the opportunity for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and political freedom, the U.S., and the West in general does not, however, have the right to say how, and on what timetable, those objectives should be achieved. \par \par \uc2  As a beneficiary of the democratic system I hope to see the time when it will be a benefit and a right enjoyed by all people throughout the region. That time is more likely to come through constructive engagement in trade and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cooperation than through myth-making, moralizing and intermittently threatening sanctions. Can you imagine the outrage in America if East Asian nations threatened to impose a boycott on U.S. goods and services until such time as easy access to guns was outlawed in that country, or Hollywood was forced to stop producing mega-violent movies? \par \par \uc2  Within the approach of constructive engagement it is appropriate, and in certain cases essential, for countries with a democratic system to express and explain concerns they may have about features in other countries. Such representations made in the course of interchanges between leaders, diplomats and business representatives are much more likely over time to have a positive influence if not projected from a platform of moral superiority and if done with an acknowledgement of weaknesses in one's own society. \par \par \uc2  Reciprocally, Asian countries should understand that little is gained by demonising the United States and the West generally as the source of many of their own emerging social problems. These problems - increasing use of drugs, crime, the breakdown of family relationships and responsibilities - are essentially the product of their own rapid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and will assume the dimensions that Asian leaders find appalling in the West unless they are smarter than we have been in recognizing and dealing with them at an early stage. \par \par \uc2  The fundamental challenges confronting mankind in the years ahead will be global in their impact and will be most pressing in the Asian region. To mention just two: (a) the environment - the International Energy Agency assesses that within fifteen years Asia will account for 75 percent of world carbon dioxide emissions; (b) the population explosion - the UN 1995 State of the Environment Report referring to a predicted doubling of the region's population in the next 44 years says: "Such an astronomical increase in human numbers is bound to trigger a volatile and unpredictable state of flux in which some surprising social and national phenomena are surely in store. The earth has never before been asked to accommodate so many new people in such a short time. The presence of over three billion human inhabitants in the region is likely to take an enormous, even catastrophic toll on living conditions in the region and terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems already under strain." \par \par \uc2  The time has surely come when we recognize that despite all our differences - real and those conjured up in fear and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  - we have a shared interest in meeting these challenges, to hand on to future generations a more prosperous and sustainable world. We will not achieve this by the West arrogating to itself a monopoly of wisdom or morality nor by authoritarian regimes believing that the winds of change will cease to blow in the years ahead. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018ds8m004oz\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
