\par\par \b \uc2  'COURT INDEPENDENCE TO REMAIN ILLUSIVE'. \b0\par\par\uc2 461 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 August 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The independence of courts will remain illusive as long as the welfare of court officials is still dependent on the government, scholars said at a seminar yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Legal observers Satya Arinanto, Erman Radjagukguk and Edwin H. Soekowati said during a dialog on politics held by the Center for Information and Development Studies, that the lack of independence was mainly because the officials are structurally under the executive branch of the bureaucracy. \par \par \uc2  "Judges' independence is determined by their structural positions. In legal court practices, the judges are supervised by the Supreme Court, while in administrative and financial management, they are supervised by the Ministry of Justice," Satya said. \par \par \uc2  "How can we expect the judges to be independent if their welfare is determined by the government, while their performance (is determined) by the Supreme Court?" he said. \par \par \uc2  He said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's long-standing doubt on the courts' independence peaked with the revelation of alleged collusion this year at the Supreme Court, which involved senior judges and officials of the Court. \par \par \uc2  "Chief Justice Soerjono's decision to settle the allegation internally has lessened \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  trust in courts," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said that the Supreme Court's reputation as the "last bastion for justice" is often cynically twisted into the "last bastion for power". \par \par \uc2  Erman Radjagukguk shared a view similar to Satya's. \par \par \uc2  "Our legal system cannot stand firm and be free from other existing systems, e.g. political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  systems," he said. \par \par \uc2  He, said, however he believed that the judicial system and judges' independence would improve in line with the increasing external pressures on Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  External factors \par \par \uc2  External factors, including the General Agreement of Trade and Tariffs and Asia-Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Forum agreements, in which Indonesia is a member, will sooner or later force the nation to improve its judicial system, he said. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Edwin said judges have frequently failed to apply legal objective norms in their decisions. \par \par \uc2  "We can see that judges consider whether the defendants and plaintiffs are rich or strong, politically weak or powerful, rather than the objective legal principle that everybody is equal before the law," he said. \par \par \uc2  This, he said, has made people reluctant to bring their conflicts to court. \par \par \uc2  "People sometimes want to deal with courts only if they have more than enough money or strong backing from influential or powerful persons," he said. \par \par \uc2  "Otherwise, they will remain quiet and only pray to God for justice, even though their rights have obviously been denied," he added. \par \par \uc2  He said that people would also meet such \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of justice when they were in conflicts with the government in the state administrative court. \par \par \uc2  "Judges in the state administrative court are also government employees," he said. (imn) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018ds8s0050b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
