\par\par \b \uc2  ANALYSTS PREDICT BUOYANT GROWTH IN 1996, 1997. \b0\par\par\uc2 603 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 October 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The Econit \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  research group predicts buoyant 7.5 percent growth for 1997, despite the political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  that could emerge. \par \par \uc2  Growth will reach 7.3 percent this year, lower than the 8.1 percent recorded last year, Econit says, attributing the slow down to the government's efforts, including monetary contractions, to cool down the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "All \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  factors, both macro and micro, seem all right, and the cooling-off tendency will continue until the first semester of next year. If everything is okay, our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will rebound in the second semester," Rizal Ramli, a director of Econit, said in announcing its \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook 1997 on Saturday. \par \par \uc2  The level of political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  can be expected to increase next year and that it will very much influence the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook, he said. \par \par \uc2  "If political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  becomes political volatility and unrest, deviations and variance of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlooks will also be greater, and we must revise downward our growth prediction." \par \par \uc2  Next year's political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and anxiety will be influenced by sociopolitical factors, including the political dynamism expected toward next year's general election, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Social and political groupings will move to strengthen their political leverage before and after the general election, as well as before the creation of a new cabinet in 1998," Rizal said. \par \par \uc2  Econit managing director Arif Arryman said there will be a great deal of non-budgetary \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and increases in the government's routine expenditures to ensure that Golkar, the ruling political group, win the election. \par \par \uc2  "Like in any other country, the government usually uses an election-driven \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . That means increasing its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  prior to the general election to ensure the win of the ruling political group," Arif said. \par \par \uc2  Such non-budgetary \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and inflated routine \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will undermine the efforts to cool down the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he warned. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund have urged Jakarta to cool down its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and thus producing a surplus in its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  by between 2 to 3 percent of gross domestic product. \par \par \uc2  Presidency \par \par \uc2  As for the country's presidency, Rizal said, Econit does not take a special view. \par \par \uc2  "Everybody knows that Golkar will win in next year's general election and the president will remain the same," he said. \par \par \uc2  Such a situation would bear specific \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  if something happened to the incumbent President Soeharto, because nobody knows who could replace him, he said. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia still relies on a personalized, not institutionalized, decision making process, in the political, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  or legal sectors; and this will increase the level of both political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Rizal said. \par \par \uc2  Political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  will influence the realization of foreign direct investment commitments. Some of the projects are very likely to be postponed, he said. \par \par \uc2  A delay in the realization of foreign investment projects would help reduce the country's imports. However, this could also reduce the government's capability to cover up the country's deepening current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's export performance will not improve significantly next year because of the strengthening of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar, Econit forecasts. \par \par \uc2  In addition, the supply response of Indonesia's exports to the improving \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in developed countries has proven to be slow, Econit said in its report. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Indonesia's exports remain dependent on markets in developed countries, especially those in the Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development (OECD), as almost 60 percent of Indonesia's total exports of $45.4 billion last year went to the OECD countries. (rid) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018dsas0023d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
