\par\par \b \uc2  GENERAL ELECTION SEEN AS NO THREAT TO BUSINESS CLIMATE. \b0\par\par\uc2 535 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 December 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Indonesia's business climate is not likely to change much after next year's general election as the results have been predicted, business executives and analysts said yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Businessman Fahmi Idris from the Kodel Group said that whatever the outcome of the election, businesses will be able to adapt to government policies. \par \par \uc2  "Some businesses actually have an influence on the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 -making process," he said at a seminar discussing business prospects after the 1997 general election. \par \par \uc2  The seminar, held to commemorate the second anniversary of the Gatra newsweekly magazine, featured other speakers, including economists Sjahrir from the Institute for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Financial Research, Didik J. Rachbini from the Institute for Development of Economics and Finance, and marketing consultant Hermawan Kartajaya. \par \par \uc2  Fahmi said that the election might cause a slight shock to, or worries within, businesses, but that their ability to adjust would protect them from harm. \par \par \uc2  However, he said, businesses may have a "change in attitude" after the year 2000 because the next elections, to be held in 2002, "will almost surely not see the re-election of President Soeharto". \par \par \uc2  "I am sure that businessmen will only start making their moves around the year 2000. At that time, they will start to lobby the next presidential candidate and people who might hold top government posts," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said that he was convinced that the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  would do a "better job" at that time. The House, he said, would refrain from simply rubber stamping any \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  proposed by the government, as it does now. \par \par \uc2  "But as long as the country is led by Pak Harto, there will be no significant change," Fahmi added. \par \par \uc2  Similarly, economist Sjahrir said not only would Indonesia's business climate not change, its problems would also remain the same. \par \par \uc2  "Even if \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth can be maintained at a high level, the distribution or focus of this growth will not be different from the past. \par \par \uc2  "The unequal accumulation of productive assets will continue and any efforts to enhance equity will be more of a symbolic gesture than a serious, well planned program," he said. \par \par \uc2  Sjahrir said partnership programs between conglomerates and small and medium enterprises would continue to fail if basic policies were not changed to support the government's efforts to narrow existing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  gaps. \par \par \uc2  He said the nine-month transition period during the election of House members in May, 1997, and the swearing-in of the new president in March, 1998, would be an unsettling period for the business sector. \par \par \uc2  "The nine-month period will be very long and during this time we will have a lame-duck government. This period will be full of political lobbying and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  concerns will be at the bottom of the government's priority list," he said. \par \par \uc2  Hermawan Kartajaya said that for the first six months of next year, most businesses have predicted a slowdown in operations and an increase in business risk. \par \par \uc2  "This slowdown will result in a six-month lag which is really not good for businesses because they must face free trade in a few years' time," he said. (pwn) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 T