\par\par \b \uc2  GOVT VOWS TO COOL DOWN  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2  By Riyadi \par \uc2 1,802 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 December 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was estimated to grow by over 7 percent this year and is projected to remain buoyant next year despite the general election in May. \par \par \uc2  The bright macroeconomic outlook, however, is overshadowed by the swelling current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which according to most analysts has reached an alarming level - almost 4 percent of the gross domestic product. \par \par \uc2  However, it is likely that inflation declined to below 7 percent this year (compared to 8.64 percent last year and 9.24 percent in 1994) despite the increases in transportation fares and minimum wages earlier this year. \par \par \uc2  Lower inflation this year will decrease inflationary expectations in 1997. \par \par \uc2  Although inflation was relatively low, the monetary authority has ruled out a substantial easing of the tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  next year. \par \par \uc2  Though the national agenda will be heavily political in view of the general election in May, most economists agree that Indonesia will still see robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of over 7 percent next year, quite similar to this year's level. \par \par \uc2  The Econit research group, for instance, has predicted 7.5 percent growth in 1997 provided that political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  does not become political volatility and unrest. \par \par \uc2  The main engine of next year's growth will be the sectors of electricity, gas and water, construction as well as manufacturing - each with a growth exceeding 10 percent. This indicates growth will still be driven by domestic demand. \par \par \uc2  Econit expects growth to reach 7.3 percent this year, lower than the 8.1 percent recorded last year, as the impact of the government's efforts to cool down the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The Institute for Development of Economics and Finance projects an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion of 7.8 percent this year and 7.4 percent next year. \par \par \uc2  Domestic demand, especially household consumption and investment, will continue to be the locomotive of growth, the institute says. \par \par \uc2  Mari E. Pangestu of the Centre for Strategic and International Studies forecasts a growth of 7.6 percent next year, up from an estimated 7.5 percent this year. \par \par \uc2  Most of the growth will be generated by the construction sector, financial services and the trade, hotel and restaurant industries, Mari said. \par \par \uc2  This year's growth, however, was very much spurred by the increasing domestic demand, as can be seen from the 26 percent expansion of the money supply - composed of currencies, demand deposits and quasi-money. \par \par \uc2  The 26 percent year-on-year growth is much higher than the government's target growth of only 17 percent for this year. \par \par \uc2  According to the Investment Coordinating Board, the amount of domestic investment commitments approved by the government surged from Rp 39.5 trillion in 1993 to Rp 53.3 trillion in 1994, Rp 69.8 trillion in 1995 and Rp 100.7 trillion this year (as of Dec. 15). \par \par \uc2  Foreign investment commitments increased from US$8.14 billion in 1993 to $23.72 billion in 1994, $39.9 billion in 1995 and dropped to $29.9 billion this year (as of Dec. 15). \par \par \uc2  Realization of investment commitments usually take place two to three years after a project is approved by the government. Therefore, 1993 and 1994 investment commitments will very likely be realized this year. \par \par \uc2  The investment board reported last week that the realization was 46.4 percent for domestic investment projects and 48.1 percent for foreign projects. \par \par \uc2  The current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  increased from $2.96 billion in 1994 (about 2 percent of gross domestic product) to $6.76 billion in 1995 (3.8 percent of gross domestic product). \par \par \uc2  Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad told the House Budgetary Commission earlier this month the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  was $4.5 billion for the first semester (April to September) of the 1996/1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Finance Saleh Afiff forecast earlier the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would increase to $8.7 billion in 1996/1997, up from the $6.8 billion envisaged in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Most analysts have predicted the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would increase to up to 4 percent of gross domestic product this year. \par \par \uc2  Senior economist Sumitro Djojohadikusumo warned early this month that the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  had reached an alarming level. \par \par \uc2  Mar'ie revealed last month that the government's foreign debt had fallen to $57.22 billion at the end of September from $59.59 billion at the end of last year. \par \par \uc2  The government's debts constitute 60 percent of the country's outstanding offshore borrowings. \par \par \uc2  To reduce its burdening debts, the government has repaid its high-interest loans using proceeds from the sale of government shares in state-owned companies and from \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  surpluses. \par \par \uc2  The government last October paid US$540.46 million of its high-interest debt ahead of schedule to multilateral agencies - the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank - and will soon amortize another $50.58 million. \par \par \uc2  If these debt prepayments can be concluded, the government will have prepaid a total $2.82 billion in foreign debts by the end of the current 1996/1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have expressed great concern over the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 's sharp increase because it happened in the first semester when oil and natural gas exports greatly exceeded the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 's expectations. \par \par \uc2  The 1996/1997 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the period of which ends in March, estimates an average oil price of $16.50 a barrel for the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. Actual prices in the first semester averaged $19.15 a barrel. \par \par \uc2  The government said every $1 increase in the price of crude oil per barrel contributes Rp 630.7 billion to its revenue from oil \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The main reason for the increase in the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  was the decline in trade surplus and the widening \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in services. \par \par \uc2  The only way to reduce the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  is through bolstering exports while curbing import growth and reducing the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in services. \par \par \uc2  In a bid to boost exports, the government introduced a major \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform package last June. The package covers the timetable for further reductions of import tariffs on 1,497 items, simplifying import and export procedures, offering more incentives to export-oriented companies and more flexibility for foreign manufacturers operating in the country. \par \par \uc2  Under the new package, the government promises to give special \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , customs and banking breaks to exporters of textiles and textile-related products, shoes, electronics, wood and rattan products and leather goods. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) Governor J. Soedradjad Djiwandono said earlier this month the cooling-down efforts by the monetary authority since late last year had produced some results. \par \par \uc2  The money supply in narrow definition (M1) had slowed down since June this year, reaching 27.5 percent in September, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  liquidity (M2) growth also slowed down to 26.1 percent, while credit growth stood at 19.8 percent. \par \par \uc2  The government's targets for M1, M2 and bank credit growth for this year were 15 percent, 17 percent and 16 percent, respectively. \par \par \uc2  Imports increased by merely 6.68 percent to US$28.28 billion during the first eight months of this year from $26.5 billion during the same period of last year. \par \par \uc2  The slow growth in imports, however, was not followed by a higher rate of growth in exports. Exports increased by only 10 percent to $31.87 billion, compared to $28.97 billion. \par \par \uc2  Last year, imports soared by 25.6 percent to $40 billion from $31.9 billion in 1994, while exports grew by 16 percent to $45.4 billion from $40 billion. \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad said the widening current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to a level of 3.8 percent of gross domestic product, was still manageable. \par \par \uc2  He contended that the surplus from the capital account was enough to finance the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the current account. He foresaw a surplus in the overall balance of payments next year. \par \par \uc2  Although the government failed to reduce the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  from swelling, it managed to slow down inflation this year, despite the 10.6 percent increase in daily minimum wages and the 9.2 percent to 66.7 percent rise in transportation fares earlier last April. \par \par \uc2  This year, inflation is likely to be checked below 7 percent, down from 8.64 percent last year and 9.24 percent in 1994. \par \par \uc2  The cumulative inflation for the first 11 months of this year reached only 5.92 percent, compared with 7.85 percent for the same period of last year. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia, hampered by high inflation rates for years, recorded monthly deflations three times this year. The month-on-month deflation rate of minus 0.61 percent was reported in March, minus 0.07 percent in July and minus 0.04 percent in September. \par \par \uc2  This year's inflation rate, however, is still higher than the government's target of 5 percent per annum. \par \par \uc2  Considering the widening current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and relatively high inflation rate, the government is expected to maintain its tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Soedradjad said the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would continue to tighten \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  liquidity through a number of instruments to pursue a "soft landing" for the country's overheating \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Monetary stabilization efforts will continue until 1997 to curb inflation and current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  so that our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow in a sustainable manner," Soedradjad said. \par \par \uc2  In its efforts to cool down the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , finance minister Mar'ie pledged the government would continue to produce a surplus in its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government has projected to secure a surplus of Rp 900 billion (US$378 million) for the current 1996/1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year, ending in March next year. \par \par \uc2  Tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , however, kept domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  high in 1996 although there has been persistent calls from a senior minister as well as the private sector for lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Deposit rates stay at some 17 percent, while lending rates stand at some 22 percent. \par \par \uc2  Economist Sjahrir predicted that the tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  - which is to become even more stringent as a result of the increase in commercial banks' reserve requirement to 5 percent next April from the current 3 percent - will force banks to increase or at least maintain their current \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The possibility of an increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the United States will put additional upward pressures on Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  A rise in domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would attract more capital inflows because of widening differentials between domestic and foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Such inflows would complicate macroeconomic management and undermine the monetary authority's efforts to cool down the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The inflows, however, would additionally support the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow high next year. \par \par \uc2  Window A: The main locomotive of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth remains the domestic market demand. \par \par \uc2  Window B: The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will still be able to post 7.5 percent growth in 1997 provided the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  does not turn into political volatility and unrest. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1996 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011018dscq0024w\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
