\par\par \b \uc2  A YEAR OF UPS AND DOWNS ON THE STOCK MARKET. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Sigma Batara Research \par \uc2 1,141 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 December 1996\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1996 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The stock market started the year bullishly with the Jakarta Composite Index (JCI) surging from a 453 low in Nov. 20, 1995 to a 630 high on April 24, 1996. \par \par \uc2  In between, it experienced two major corrections. The first correction of 8.7 percent (from 592 to 544.5) occurred from March 4 to March 11. It was triggered by a declining trade surplus and a higher-than-expected February inflation rate. Later that week, along with most regional markets, it followed the U.S. stock market plunge after high U.S. unemployment created \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over a possible U.S. interest rate cut. \par \par \uc2  But the index rebounded just as quickly. It was back to 587.3 by March 19. The second correction occurred in the first week of May with the market falling from 629.5 to 599.7. This was triggered by the weekend's death of First Lady Tien Soeharto. Later that week, a U.S. market correction because of better-than-expected U.S. GDP growth also affected the local market. \par \par \uc2  Bearish sentiment hit the market in June because of several domestic events. Investors sold out of the secondary market to subscribe to the first wave of initial \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offerings on the primary market. This brought the market down more than 40 points from 625. \par \par \uc2  The market rebounded 25 points by the end of June before worry about President Soeharto's health in early July brought the market down 25 points. In late July, there was more selling after the July 27 riots in Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Down 50 points to 533, the market swung back and forth wildly between 560 and 533 before moving into a narrow range around 550 in early September. \par \par \uc2  The market rebounded in September. The JCI rallied from 550 in mid-September to 590 in early October. The expectation and realization of unchanged U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  was a major force behind the bullish sentiment. \par \par \uc2  The following week the index dropped to 570, before rallying at the end of October to a 620 high because of favorable regional sentiment caused by expectations that U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would stay flat in the long term. \par \par \uc2  After a small correction the market rallied again, passing the year high of 630, spurred by BNI's listing, the year's only privatization. \par \par \uc2  After some small corrections, the market is expected to end the year at around 630. \par \par \uc2  Fundamentals \par \par \uc2  After experiencing 8.1 percent growth in 1995, gross domestic product (GDP) is set to grow more slowly. The figure has raised fears of an overheating \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The government has subsequently tightened its rein on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mainly through contractionary monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We project 7.5 percent growth in 1996 and 7.4 percent in 1997. \par \par \uc2  Tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  kept domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  high in 1996. We project deposit \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will stay at 17.3 percent until the end of the year. In 1997, the following factors will affect \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 : \par \par \uc2  1. The possibility of an interest rate rise in the U.S. will put upward pressure on Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  2. Reduced inflation in 1996 will decrease inflationary expectations in 1997, putting downward pressure on domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  3. Warming political pressure (during election time in May 1997) will slightly raise country risk. \par \par \uc2  In our opinion, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 1997 will stay about the same as in 1996. \par \par \uc2  Tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in an open \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  like Indonesia's creates significant capital inflow to take advantage of high interest rate differentials. A large supply of the U.S. dollars has appreciated the rupiah against the American greenback. This situation has occurred since March 1996. \par \par \uc2  * \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , has refused to intervene in the foreign exchange market. This move is consistent with its effort to cool the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  (but detrimental to export competitiveness). \par \par \uc2  * By the end of 1996, we think exchange (spot) rates will be Rp 2,350/US$. At the end of 1997, we project the exchange rate will be Rp 2,470/US$, implying 5 percent depreciation. This will compensate slow depreciation in 1996 and maintain the competitiveness of exports. \par \par \uc2  In 1996, the balance of payments will deteriorate further, albeit more slowly. We project a current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of US$ 9.1 billion in 1996 (4.23 percent of GDP) but a much improved \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of $6.8 billion in 1997 (2.88 percent of GDP). \par \par \uc2  Investment Outlook \par \par \uc2  Next year the market should perform well with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  growing more than 7 percent and inflation remaining below 7 percent. Domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are expected to drop at least in the first-half of 1997. U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are expected to stay unchanged for some time. Indonesian privatization will always be the focus of attention. We expect Jasa Marga, Aneka Tambang and PLN subsidiaries to be floated next year. \par \par \uc2  The stock market is also trying to improve. Next year the Jakarta Stock Exchange is expected to go scriptless. This should improve liquidity and reduce administration costs. We also see more domestic investor, retail and institutional participation. Retail transactions will be boosted by margin trading, while institutional transactions will be boosted by the newly formed open-ended mutual funds. \par \par \uc2  But any negative political or social development could spark a market plunge. This is particularly relevant next year with the general election on May 29, 1997. \par \par \uc2  A careful investment strategy is therefore warranted, although investment in Indonesia remains attractive. \par \par \uc2  But the political situation in the short-term may cause market volatility. For 1997, we recommend avoiding politically sensitive stocks. You should invest in stocks that will benefit from domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and have minimal political risk. \par \par \uc2  Table: \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Figures and Forecasts \par \par \uc2  1994 1995 1996F 1997F \par \par \uc2  Growth (%) \par \par \uc2  GDP 7.3 8.1 7.5 7.4 \par \par \uc2  Private Consumption 5.8 6.2 6.0 7.0 \par \par \uc2  Govt Consumption 2.9 6.4 4.9 5.0 \par \par \uc2  Investment 15.4 23.9 6.7 14.5 \par \par \uc2  Exports 7.3 13.39 14.0 10.0 \par \par \uc2  Imports 13.3 24.6 18.6 16.7 \par \par \uc2  Population & Income \par \par \uc2  GDP (US$bn) 171.52 192.98 214.73 235.69 \par \par \uc2  Population (m) 191.8 195.6 199.5 203.9 \par \par \uc2  GDP per capita (US$) 894.3 986.6 1076.3 1155.9 \par \par \uc2  Inflation (%) 9.4 8.64 6.9 7.3 \par \par \uc2  Financial Indicators \par \par \uc2  Exc. Rate (Rp/US$) 2200 2308 23